res Sanskriet Series 1983. Mysore 1946\n*{{IAST|N\u0101\u1e6dy\u01ce \u015ah\u0101str\u01ce}} (of Bharat\u01ce) (chapters 28, 29 and 38 deal with music) Text only: Benares, 1929; with text and commentary of Abhinav\u01ce Gupt\u01ce: Barode, 1926\n*{{Citation | last=[[Matanga]] | title=Brhaddeshu = Trivandrum Sanskrit Series, XCIV (1928), 82\u2013133}}\n** Ragas and raginis by Amiyanath Sanyal (English) ORIENT LONGMANS 1959 printed by S.C.Ghosh, Calcutta Press, Wellington Squate, Calcutta  (Link: www.dli.ernet.in)\n** Sangita Ratnakara of Sarangadeva (Raga Adyaya)  ( -do- )\n-->\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://raag-hindustani.com/Scales1.html A step-by-step introduction to the concept of r\u0101ga for beginners]\n*[http://www.parrikar.org/ Rajan Parrikar Music Archive \u2013 detailed analyses of r\u0101gas backed by rare audio recordings]\n*[http://www.soundofindia.com/raagas.asp Comprehensive reference on r\u0101gas]\n*[http://moutal.eu/indian-music.html Hindustani Raga Sangeet Online] A rare collection of more than 800 audio & video archives from 1902. Radio programs dedicated to famous ragas.\n*[http://webspace.webring.com/people/dv/vasudevanvrv/carnatic/raagams.htm Online quick reference of r\u0101gams] in Carnatic music.\n{{Hindustani Classical Music page end}}\n{{R\u0101gas as per Performance Time}}\n{{Melakarta ragas|state=collapsed}}\n{{Janya}}\n{{Melody types}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raga}}\n[[Category:Hindustani ragas]]\n[[Category:Hindustani music terminology]]\n[[Category:Musical terminology]]\n[[Category:Modes]]\n[[Category:Ragas| ]]\n", "name_user": "Sidharth V Maurya", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added an elaborate description of the skeleton of a raga.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raga"}
{"title_page": "Home Alone", "text_new": "{{short description|1990 film directed by Chris Columbus}} \n{{About|the first film in the series|the series|Home Alone (franchise)|other uses|Home Alone (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2019}}{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Home Alone\n| image          = Home alone poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]]\n| producer       = [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]]\n| writer         = John Hughes\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|<!-- Per [[Template:Infobox film]], only the actors on the film's billing block should be listed. -->\n* [[Macaulay Culkin]]\n* [[Joe Pesci]]\n* [[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]]\n* [[John Heard (actor)|John Heard]]\n* [[Catherine O'Hara]]\n}}\n| music          = [[John Williams]]\n| cinematography = [[Julio Macat]]\n| editing        = [[Raja Gosnell]]\n| studio         = Hughes Entertainment\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1990|11|10|Chicago|1990|11|16|United States}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 102:36--><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227075147/https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/home-alone-1970-3|title=HOME ALONE (PG)|last=|first=|date=|website=British Board of Film Classification|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/home-alone-1970-3|archive-date=February 27, 2020|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $18 million<ref name=mojo>{{cite web |title = Home Alone (1990) |url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200211151647/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3629745665/weekend/ |archive-url = http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=homealone.htm |website = [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate = November 19, 2011 |archive-date = February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n| gross          = $476.7 million<ref name=mojo />\n}}\n\n'''''Home Alone''''' is a 1990 American [[comedy film]] written and produced by [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]] and directed by [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]]. It stars [[Macaulay Culkin]], [[Joe Pesci]], [[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]], [[John Heard (actor)|John Heard]], and [[Catherine O'Hara]]. The film follows an eight-year-old boy (Culkin), who must defend his home from two burglars (Pesci and Stern) after his family mistakenly leaves him behind on their Christmas vacation. It was filmed between February and May 1990, in an array of locations. The film was originally meant to be a production from [[Warner Bros.]], but was changed to a [[20th Century Fox]] production when Hughes exceeded a $10 million budget that he promised for the film with Warner Bros. \n\n''Home Alone'' premiered on November 10, 1990, in Chicago, and was released wider in the United States on November 16, 1990. With a total gross of $476.7 million, it was the highest-grossing live-action comedy ever, and held the record until it was overtaken by ''[[The Hangover Part II]]'' in 2011. The film received two [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor in a Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] for Culkin, as well as two [[Academy Award]] nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], which was composed by [[John Williams]], and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"Somewhere in My Memory\". Despite receiving mixed reviews from critics on its initial release, ''Home Alone'' has been hailed as a holiday classic among audiences and is often regarded as one of the best Christmas films ever made.\n\n''Home Alone'' spawned a successful [[Home Alone (franchise)|film franchise]] that started with the 1992 sequel ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York]]'', which is the only ''Home Alone'' sequel to have most of the original cast reprising their roles.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- NOTICE: Plot summaries should be 400-700 words. See WP:FILMPLOT. Do not add unnecessary detail to this section. -->\nThe McCallister family is preparing to spend Christmas in Paris, gathering at Peter and Kate's home in a [[Chicago]] [[Chicago land|suburb]] on the night before their departure. Peter and Kate's youngest son, Kevin, is the subject of ridicule by his older siblings. Later, Kevin accidentally ruins the family dinner and their flight tickets to Paris after a scuffle with his older brother Buzz, resulting in him getting sent to the [[attic]] of the house as a punishment, where he berates Kate and wishes that his family would disappear. During the night, heavy winds damage the power lines, which causes a [[power outage]] and resets the alarm clocks, causing the family to oversleep. In the confusion and rush to get to the airport, Kevin is accidentally left behind.\n\nKevin wakes to find the house empty and, thinking that his wish has come true, is overjoyed with his newfound freedom. However, he soon becomes frightened by his next door neighbor, Old Man Marley, who is rumored to be a [[serial killer]] who murdered his own family, as well as the \"Wet Bandits\", Harry and Marv, a pair of burglars who have been breaking into other vacant houses in the neighborhood and have targeted the McCallisters' house. Kevin tricks them into thinking that his family is still home, forcing them to put their plans on hold.\n\nKate realizes mid-flight that Kevin was left behind, and upon arrival in Paris, the family discovers that all flights for the next two days are booked. Peter and the rest of the family stay in his brother's apartment in Paris, while Kate manages to get a flight back to the United States, but only gets as far as [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]. She attempts to book a flight to Chicago, but again, everything is booked. Unable to accept this, Kate is overheard by Gus Polinski, the lead member of a traveling polka band, who offers to let her travel with them to [[Chicago]] on their way to [[Milwaukee]] in a moving van, which she gratefully accepts.\n\nMeanwhile, Harry and Marv finally realize that Kevin is home alone, and on Christmas Eve, Kevin overhears them discussing plans to break into his house that night. Kevin starts to miss his family and asks the local [[Santa Claus]] impersonator if he could bring his family back for Christmas. He goes to church and watches a [[choir]] perform, then meets Old Man Marley, who dispels the rumors about him. He points out his granddaughter in the choir, whom he never gets to meet, as he and his son are estranged; Kevin suggests that he should reconcile with his son.\n\nKevin returns home and rigs the house with [[booby trap]]s to take on the burglars. Harry and Marv break in, spring the traps, and suffer various injuries. While the duo pursues Kevin around the house, he calls the police and flees, then lures Harry and Marv into a neighboring home which they previously broke into. They ambush him and prepare to get their revenge, but Marley intervenes and knocks them unconscious with his snow shovel. The police arrive and arrest Harry and Marv, having identified all the houses that they broke into due to Marv's destructive characteristic of flooding them.\n\nOn Christmas Day, Kevin is disappointed to find that his family is still gone. He then hears Kate enter the house and call for him; they reconcile and are soon joined by Peter, Buzz, Jeff, Megan, and Linnie, who waited in Paris until they could obtain a direct flight to Chicago. Kevin keeps silent about his encounter with Harry and Marv, although Peter finds Harry's knocked-out gold tooth. Kevin then observes Marley reuniting with his son, daughter-in-law, and granddaughter. Marley notices Kevin, and the pair wave to each other.\n\n==Cast==\n<!--ACCORDING TO THE END CREDITS OF THE FILM per WP:FILMCAST-->\n{{cast list|\n* [[Macaulay Culkin]] as Kevin, a rambunctious eight-year-old with a penchant for creating harmful inventions\n* [[Joe Pesci]] as Harry, a short and hotheaded thief who targets the McCallisters' home with Marv\n* [[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]] as Marv, a tall and dim-witted thief who targets the McCallisters' home with Harry\n* [[John Heard (actor)|John Heard]] as Peter, Kevin's father\n* [[Roberts Blossom]] as Marley, Kevin's elderly neighbor\n* [[Catherine O'Hara]] as Kate, Kevin's mother and Peter's wife\n* [[Angela Goethals]] as Linnie, Kevin's older sister\n* [[Devin Ratray]] as Buzz, Kevin's oldest brother who often gets him into trouble\n* [[Gerry Bamman]] as Uncle Frank, Peter's older brother\n* [[Hillary Wolf]] as Megan, Kevin's oldest sister\n* [[John Candy]] as Gus Polinski, polka performer who helps Kate\n* [[Larry Hankin]] as Officer Balzak\n* [[Michael C. Maronna]] as Jeff, Kevin's older brother\n* [[Kristin Minter]] as Heather, Kevin's oldest cousin\n* Daiana Campeanu as Sondra, Kevin's older cousin\n* Jedidiah Cohen as Rod, Kevin's older cousin\n* [[Kieran Culkin]] as Fuller, Kevin's youngest cousin\n* [[Senta Moses]] as Tracy, Kevin's older cousin\n* [[Anna Slotky]] as Brook, Kevin's younger cousin\n* Terrie Snell as Aunt Leslie, Uncle Frank's wife\n* Jeffrey Wiseman as Mitch Murphy, 8-year-old neighbor whom Heather mistakes for Kevin during the headcount\n* Virginia Smith as Georgette, Kevin's aunt, wife of Uncle Rob, and mother of Heather and Steffan\n* [[Matt Doherty (actor)|Matt Doherty]] as Steffan, Kevin's older cousin\n* [[Ralph Foody]] as Gangster #1 (Johnny), character in the film ''Angels with Filthy Souls''\n* Michael Guido as Gangster #2 (Snakes), character in the film ''Angels with Filthy Souls''\n* Ray Toler as Uncle Rob, Kevin's uncle, younger brother of Peter and Uncle Frank, and father of Heather and Steffan\n* [[Billie Bird]] as Woman in Airport, Irene, who sells Kate her ticket to Dallas\n* [[Bill Erwin]] as Man in Airport, Ed, Irene's husband who agrees with Irene's ticket sale\n* [[Gerry Becker]] as Officer #1\n* [[Alan Wilder (actor)|Alan Wilder]] as Scranton Ticket Agent\n* [[Hope Davis]] as French Ticket Agent\n* [[Kenneth Hudson Campbell]] as Santa, Santa Claus impersonator seen by Kevin\n}}\nCredits adapted from Rotten Tomatoes.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\" />\n==Production==\n===Development===\nThe conception of ''Home Alone'' arose from a personal dilemma that producer John Hughes had faced. Hughes explained that \"I was going away on vacation, and making a list of everything I didn\u2019t want to forget. I thought, 'well, I'd better not forget my kids.' Then I thought, 'what if I left my 10-year-old son at home? What would he do?{{Single+double}}<ref name=\"conception\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190519015208/http://time.com/4105161/home-alone-1990/|title=How John Hughes Came Up With Home Alone|last=|first=|date=November 16, 2015|website=Time|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://time.com/4105161/home-alone-1990/|archive-date=May 19, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Hughes then wrote eight pages of notes that developed into the screenplay of the film.<ref name=conception/> Imagining that children are naturally most scared of robbers, Hughes also worked that aspect into the plot of the film.<ref name=conception/>\n\n''Home Alone'' was initially a [[Warner Bros.]] production. Hughes had promised the studio he could make the movie for no more than $10 million, considerably less than most feature film production budgets of that era. Concerned that the film might exceed that amount, even minimally, and that Warner would insist on keeping to it, Hughes met secretly with [[20th Century Fox]] before production to see if they would be interested in funding the project if Warner proved as inflexible as the producer feared. A copy of the script was \"clandestinely\" delivered to Fox, according to [[executive producer]] Scott Rosenfelt, bypassing the legal restrictions that would have otherwise prevented Fox from seeing it until the project was in [[Turnaround (filmmaking)|turnaround]].<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\">{{cite news|last=Bucklow|first=Andrew|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212233609/https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/home-alone-secrets-revealed-in-netflix-show-the-movies-that-made-us/news-story/7dd4896680c9c157e18b7f4e264c418f|title=''Home Alone'' secrets revealed in Netflix show 'The Movies That Made Us'|date=December 4, 2019|newspaper=[[news.com.au]]|accessdate=December 4, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/home-alone-secrets-revealed-in-netflix-show-the-movies-that-made-us/news-story/7dd4896680c9c157e18b7f4e264c418f|archive-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in production, the film's budget grew to $14.7 million, well past the limit Warner had imposed. The studio demanded that it be cut by $1.2 million; the producers responded with a memo arguing that the budget could not be cut any further. Warner, unconvinced, shut down production the next day. It quickly resumed as Fox took up Hughes on his earlier offer. The final budget would grow to $18 million.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" />\n\nHughes had originally asked [[Patrick Read Johnson]] to direct, but he was already committed to ''[[Spaced Invaders]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=John Hughes: A Life in Film|last=Honeycutt|first=Kirk|publisher=Race Point Publishing|year=2015|isbn=978-1631060229|location=|pages=}}</ref> He then turned to Chris Columbus, who had left ''[[National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation]]'' before shooting started, because of a personality clash with starring actor [[Chevy Chase]], who Columbus said treated him \"like dirt\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406032958/https://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/December-2015/Home-Alone/|title=Holy Cow, Home Alone Is 25!|last=|first=|date=November 10, 2015|website=|publisher=chicagomag.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/December-2015/Home-Alone/|archive-date=April 6, 2020|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Hughes then gave him the script for both ''Home Alone'' and ''[[Reach the Rock]]''; Columbus accepted the former, as he found it funnier and liked the Christmas theme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219083024/https://www.vulture.com/2015/11/columbus-directed-home-alone-because-chevy-chase.html|title=Chris Columbus Directed Home Alone Instead of Christmas Vacation Because He Met Chevy Chase|last1=Madison III|first1=Ira|date=November 10, 2015|website=Vulture|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/11/columbus-directed-home-alone-because-chevy-chase.html|archive-date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"EW2016\" /> Columbus became the director of the film.<ref name=\"EW2016\" />\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Macaulay Culkin 1991 B.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Macaulay Culkin]] (pictured in 1991), was the child star of the film.]]\nHughes suggested to Columbus that they cast [[Macaulay Culkin]] in the main role, because of his experience with the child actor while shooting ''[[Uncle Buck]]''. Columbus met with other actors for the part, by his count \"hundreds and hundreds\" (actually 200), as he felt it was his \"directorial presponsibility\".<ref name=\"EW2016\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229151131/https://ew.com/article/2015/11/06/home-alone-turns-25-chris-columbus/|title=Home Alone turns 25: A deep dive with director Chris Columbus|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Amy|date=November 6, 2015|website=Entertainment Weekly|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/11/06/home-alone-turns-25-chris-columbus|archive-date=December 29, 2019|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Columbus finally met with Culkin and agreed he was the right choice for the role.<ref name=EW2016/> \n\nFor the role of Harry, one of the bandits, [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Jon Lovitz]] were considered for the role. After both rejected it, [[Joe Pesci]] accepted it.<ref name=\":2\" /> The role of Uncle Frank was originally written for [[Kelsey Grammer]], but given to [[Gerry Bamman]] when Grammer was unavailable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221155545/https://www.glamour.com/story/15-facts-about-home-alone|title=15 Fascinating Facts You Never Knew About Home Alone|last=Eidell|first=Lynsey|date=November 16, 2015|website=Glamour|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.glamour.com/story/15-facts-about-home-alone|archive-date=February 21, 2020|access-date=February 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221155549/https://www.looper.com/33705/cast-home-alone-today/|title=Where the cast of Home Alone is today|last=Moore|first=Trent|date=July 22, 2017|website=Looper.com|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.looper.com/33705/cast-home-alone-today/|archive-date=February 21, 2020|access-date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]] was cast as Marv, but before shooting started, he was told that the production schedule had been extended from six weeks to eight. He was told there was no money in the budget for a pay increase he sought, so he quit. [[Daniel Roebuck]] was quickly hired to replace him, but after two days of rehearsal, Columbus did not see any chemistry between him and Pesci and decided to bring back Stern.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" /> Roebuck later admitted that, although he was upset to be fired from the production, he now believes the experience to be \"such a little blip of unimportance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204183429/https://mediamikes.com/2010/06/interview-with-daniel-roebuck/|title=Interview with Daniel Roebuck|last=Gencarelli|first=Mike|date=June 9, 2010|website=MediaMikes|publisher=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://mediamikes.com/2010/06/interview-with-daniel-roebuck/|archive-date=December 4, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[John Candy]] had only one day to film his scenes; it took 23 hours. He was paid $414, since he did the film as a favor to Hughes. In return, he was the only actor Hughes allowed to go off-script {{En dash}} according to Columbus, all his dialogue was improvised.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" />\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Home Alone House.jpg|thumb|The ''Home Alone'' house in [[Winnetka, Illinois]].|alt=|left]]\n[[Principal photography]] took place between February and May 1990.<ref>Weekly Variety Magazine; February 14, 1990; Page 28</ref><ref>Daily Variety Magazine; May 8, 1990; Page 18</ref> Some scenes were shot in a three-story single-family house located at 671 Lincoln Avenue<ref name= \"sold2012\">{{cite web| title= ''Home Alone'' House Sells For $1.585 Million| url= http://www.chicagonow.com/getting-real/2012/03/home-alone-house-sells-for-1-585-million/ | date= March 9, 2012 | first=Gary|last= Lucido| work= Chicago Tribune | accessdate=March 11, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310170239/http://www.chicagonow.com/getting-real/2012/03/home-alone-house-sells-for-1-585-million/|archive-date=March 10, 2012}}</ref> in the [[North Shore (Chicago)|North Shore]] village of [[Winnetka, Illinois|Winnetka]], where Hughes's previous films ''[[The Breakfast Club|Breakfast Club]]'',  ''[[Ferris Bueller's Day Off]]'', ''[[Sixteen Candles]]'', ''[[Planes, Trains & Automobiles]]'', ''[[She's Having a Baby]]'', and ''[[Uncle Buck]]'' had also been shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522193126/http://movie-locations.com/movies/h/Home-Alone.php|title=Home Alone filming locations|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=movie-locations.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/h/homealone.html|archive-date=May 22, 2019|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> The kitchen in the film was [[location filming|shot on location]], along with the main staircase, basement, attic and most of the first floor landing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movielocationsguide.com/Home_Alone_2:_Lost_in_New_York/filming_locations|title=Home Alone 2: Lost in New York Filming Locations|accessdate=June 15, 2008|publisher=movielocationsguide.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117153723/http://www.movielocationsguide.com/Home_Alone_2:_Lost_in_New_York/filming_locations|archive-date=November 17, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The tree house in the back yard was built specifically for the film and dismantled after filming ended.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite magazine|last=Wood|first=Jennifer|date=November 16, 2015|title=25 Things You Might Not Know About Home Alone|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406160806/https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/60262/25-things-you-might-not-know-about-home-alone|magazine=Mental Floss|page=|pages=|doi=|pmid=|archive-url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/60262/25-things-you-might-not-know-about-home-alone|archive-date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref> All the other interiors were duplicated on a [[soundstage]] to allow more room for equipment and crew. It was built in the gym and empty swimming pool of the former [[New Trier High School]] building, previously used by Hughes for ''Uncle Buck'' and ''Ferris Bueller's Day Off'', where the production company had already set up its offices.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" /> The scenes inside the church were shot at Grace Episcopal Church in [[Oak Park, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Weddings at Grace|website=Grace Oak Park |url=https://www.graceoakpark.org/Weddings_at_Grace.html|url-status=dead|archivedate=May 8, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508234005/https://www.graceoakpark.org/Weddings_at_Grace.html}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Angels with Filthy Souls}}For the [[Story within a story#Film within a film|film within a film]], ''Angels with Filthy Souls'' (a parody of the 1938 crime film ''[[Angels with Dirty Faces]]''), shooting took only one day. To create the illusion that the film was a 1940s [[mob film|gangster film]], the scene was filmed with black-and-white negative film and Johnny's office used authentic items from that era.<ref name=\"Vanity Fair\">{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Darryn|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113105148/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/12/home-alone-gangster-movie|title=\"Merry Christmas, Ya Filthy Animal\": Inside the Making of Home Alone's Fake Gangster Movie|date=December 22, 2015|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=November 20, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/12/home-alone-gangster-movie|archive-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCinematographer [[Julio Macat]] recalled that Pesci was more difficult to work with than Culkin. The older actor believed some of the dialogue was not of a quality commensurate with his acting ability. He also resented the early unit calls, since they prevented him from starting his day with nine holes of golf as he preferred to do.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" /> After he took the [[assistant director]] by the collar one day to complain about this, daily call times were moved back from 7 to 9 a.m. to accommodate his rounds.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reilly|first=Tim|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206125647/https://www.golf.com/news/2019/12/02/joe-pesci-demanded-call-time-change-to-play-golf-while-filming-home-alone/|title=Joe Pesci demanded call time change to play golf while filming Home Alone|date=December 2, 2019|newspaper=[[Golf (magazine)|Golf]]|accessdate=December 4, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.golf.com/news/2019/12/02/joe-pesci-demanded-call-time-change-to-play-golf-while-filming-home-alone/|archive-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref> On the other end of the schedule, the crew had limited time to film the many nighttime scenes, since Culkin could not work any later than 10 p.m. due to his age.<ref name=EW2016/>\n\nOn the set, Pesci and Stern both had difficulty refraining from swear words, which became annoying to Pesci, since Culkin was on set as well. In fact, the only swear word that made it into the film was \"shit\", accidentally said by Daniel Stern when his shoe fell through the doggy door.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Snopek|first=Amy|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406160808/https://www.buzzfeed.com/amysno/17-things-you-didnt-know-about-home-alone-gk57|title=17 Things You Didn't Know About \"Home Alone\"|date=November 15, 2013|work=BuzzFeed|access-date=April 5, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/amysno/17-things-you-didnt-know-about-home-alone-gk57|archive-date=April 6, 2020|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614162658/https://www.buzzfeed.com/terripous/youre-what-the-french-like-to-call-les-incompetent|title=24 Things You Probably Didn't Know About \"Home Alone\"|last=Pous|first=Terri|date=December 4, 2016|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/terripous/youre-what-the-french-like-to-call-les-incompetent|archive-date=June 14, 2019|access-date=April 5, 2018}}</ref> Pesci's use of \"cartoon cursing\", or menacing gibberish, garnered comparisons to ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' character [[Yosemite Sam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/archives/where-joe-pesci-saw-a-connection-between-looney-tunes-and-home-alone-1.4940775|title=Where Joe Pesci saw a connection between Looney Tunes and Home Alone|publisher=cbc.ca|date=December 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211185216/https://www.cbc.ca/archives/where-joe-pesci-saw-a-connection-between-looney-tunes-and-home-alone-1.4940775|archive-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film's stunts also created tension for the crew during shooting. Columbus said, \"Every time the stunt guys did one of those stunts it wasn't funny. We'd watch it, and I would just pray that the guys were alive.\"<ref name=\"EW2016\" /> Stunts were originally prepared with safety harnesses, but because of their visibility on camera, the film's final stunts were performed without them.<ref name=\"EW2016\" /> According to ''[[BuzzFeed|Buzzfeed]]'', an injury had occurred between Pesci and Culkin during one of the rehearsals where \"Harry tries to bite off Kevin's finger.\" Culkin still has the scar.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Music===\n{{main|Home Alone: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack}}\nInitially Columbus hoped to have [[Bruce Broughton]] score the films, and early posters listed him as the composer. However, Broughton was busy with ''[[The Rescuers Down Under]]'', and he had to cancel at the last minute.<ref name=EW2016/> Columbus was later able to get in touch with [[Steven Spielberg]], who helped him contact [[John Williams]] to produce the final score.<ref name=EW2016/> Christmas songs, such as \"[[O Holy Night]]\" and \"[[Carol of the Bells]]\", are featured prominently in the film, as well as the film's theme song \"Somewhere in My Memory\". The soundtrack was released by [[Sony Classical]] on cassette on December 4, 1990,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202083813/https://www.amazon.com/Home-Alone-Originl-Soundtrack-Various/dp/B0000027BS/|title=Home Alone-Original Soundtrack|last=|first=|date=|website=Amazon|publisher=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.amazon.com/Home-Alone-Originl-Soundtrack-Various/dp/B0000027BS/|archive-date=February 2, 2015|accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref> and on CD on May 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726154742/https://www.amazon.com/Home-Alone-Original-Picture-Soundtrack/dp/B0000027BR|title=Home Alone: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|last=|first=|date=|website=Amazon|publisher=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.amazon.com/Home-Alone-Original-Picture-Soundtrack/dp/B0000027BR/|archive-date=July 26, 2018|accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\n''Home Alone'' was first premiered in Chicago on November 10, 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531063056/https://patch.com/illinois/winnetka/home-alone-25-years-later-how-it-all-began|title='Home Alone' 25 Years Later, And How it All Began|last=Moran|first=Tim|date=November 13, 2015|website=|publisher=patch.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://patch.com/illinois/winnetka/home-alone-25-years-later-how-it-all-began|archive-date=May 31, 2019|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> It was given a wide release on November 16, 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405092005/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Home-Alone#tab=summary|title=Home Alone (1990)|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=The Numbers|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Home-Alone#tab=summary|archive-date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> ''Home Alone'' was first released by [[20th Century Fox]] on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] on August 23, 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411175534/https://ew.com/article/1991/08/23/home-alone-3/|title=Home Alone|last=Burr|first=Ty|date=August 23, 1991|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://ew.com/article/1991/08/23/home-alone-3/|archive-date=April 11, 2020|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> It was later released on [[DVD]] on October 5, 1999 as a basic package.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130021308/https://www.moviefone.com/movie/home-alone/3777/main/|title=Home Alone (1990)|last=|first=|date=October 5, 1999|website=|publisher=moviefone.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.moviefone.com/movie/home-alone/3777/main/|archive-date=November 30, 2017|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The film was released on [[Blu-ray]] on December 2, 2008, titled Family Fun Edition,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104063120/https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Home-Alone-Blu-ray/1914/|title=Home Alone Blu-ray Family Fun Edition|last=|first=|date=December 2, 2008|website=|publisher=blu-ray.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Home-Alone-Blu-ray/1914/|archive-date=January 4, 2020|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> and was released alongside ''Home Alone 2: Lost in New York'' in a collection pack on October 5, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161212114505/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Home-Alone-Collection-Blu-ray/15620/|title=Home Alone Collection Blu-ray Home Alone / Home Alone 2: Lost in New York|last=|first=|date=October 5, 2010|website=|publisher=blu-ray.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Home-Alone-Collection-Blu-ray/15620/|archive-date=December 12, 2016|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The film was reissued again on DVD and Blu-ray on October 6, 2015, alongside all five ''Home Alone'' franchise films, titled Home Alone: 25th Anniversary Ultimate Collector's Christmas Edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813014236/https://www.tribute.ca/news/home-alone-25th-anniversary-ultimate-collectors-christmas-edition-on-blu-ray-and-dvd/2015/10/06/|title=Home Alone: 25th Anniversary Ultimate Collector\u2019s Christmas Edition on Blu-ray and DVD|last=Fernandes|first=Marriska|date=October 6, 2015|website=|publisher=tribute.ca|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.tribute.ca/news/home-alone-25th-anniversary-ultimate-collectors-christmas-edition-on-blu-ray-and-dvd/2015/10/06/|archive-date=August 13, 2019|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Home Alone'' grossed $285.8 million in the United States and Canada and $190.9 million in other countries for a worldwide total of $476.7 million, against a production budget of $18 million.<ref name=mojo /> In its opening weekend, ''Home Alone'' grossed $17 million from 1,202 theaters, averaging $14,211 per site and just 6% of the final total and added screens over the next six weeks, with a peak screen count of 2,174 during its eighth weekend at the start of January 1991.<ref name=\"Forbes\" /> ''Home Alone'' proved so popular that it stayed in theaters well past the Christmas season. It was the {{Abbr|No.|Number}} 1 film at the box office for 12 straight weeks, from its release weekend of November 16\u201318, 1990 through the weekend of February 1\u20133, 1991.<ref>{{cite news|last=Broeske|first=Pat H.|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411145540/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-01-14-ca-310-story.html|title=Home Alone in 9th Week as No. 1 Film : Movies: 'Godfather Part III' takes dramatic slide from second to sixth place in its third week out. 'Awakenings' is in second.|date=January 14, 1991|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 1, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-01-14-ca-310-story.html|archive-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614122520/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/16/home-alone-at-25-how-i-forgave-a-mediocre-movie-for-becoming-a-box-office-champion/|title='Home Alone' At 25: How I Forgave A Mediocre Movie For Becoming A Box Office Champion|author=Mendelson|first=Scott|date=November 16, 2015|work=[[Forbes]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/16/home-alone-at-25-how-i-forgave-a-mediocre-movie-for-becoming-a-box-office-champion/|archive-date=June 14, 2018|accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref> It was dethroned from the top spot when ''[[Sleeping with the Enemy (film)|Sleeping with the Enemy]]'' opened with $13 million.<ref name=\"Forbes\" /> It nevertheless remained a top ten draw at the box office until the weekend of April 26 that year, which was well past Easter weekend. It made two more appearances in the top ten (the weekend of May 31 \u2013 June 2 and the weekend of June 14\u201316) before finally falling out of the top ten.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405001943/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3629745665/weekend/|title=Home Alone (1990) - Weekend Box Office Results|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=homealone.htm|archive-date=April 5, 2020|accessdate=December 24, 2007}}</ref> After over nine months into its run, the film had earned 16x its debut weekend and ended up making a final gross of $285,761,243, the top-grossing film of its year in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061113051007/http://movies.go.com/boxoffice?cat=1990|title=Movie box office results for the top 50 movies of 1990|last=|first=|date=|website=Movies.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://movies.go.com/boxoffice?cat=1990|archive-date=November 13, 2006|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The film is listed in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as the highest-grossing live-action comedy ever<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714122844/https://movie-gazette.com/1081|title=Home Alone - Movie Review|last=Panton|first=Gary|date=December 13, 2004|website=Movie Gazette|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://movie-gazette.com/1081|archive-date=July 4, 2011|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> and held the record until it was overtaken by ''[[The Hangover Part II]]'' in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003222536/https://www.etonline.com/home-alone-reboot-in-the-works-at-disney-130001|title='Home Alone' Reboot In the Works at Disney|last=Calvario|first=Liz|date=August 6, 2019|website=Entertainment Tonight|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.etonline.com/home-alone-reboot-in-the-works-at-disney-130001|archive-date=October 3, 2019|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy the time it had run its course in theaters, ''Home Alone'' was the [[List of highest-grossing films|third-highest-grossing film of all time worldwide]], as well as in [[List of highest-grossing films in Canada and the United States|the United States and Canada]] behind only ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' ($322 million at the time) and ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' ($399 million at that time), according to the home video box. [[Box Office Mojo]] estimates that the film sold over 67.7 million tickets in the United States.<ref name=mojo /> It was also the highest-grossing Christmas film until it was surpassed by ''[[The Grinch (film)|Dr. Seuss' The Grinch]]'' in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619183940/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/12/22/top-grossing-christmas-films-time/?frame=3136318|title=The top-grossing Christmas films of all time|date=December 25, 2016|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=April 11, 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/picture-galleries/11309676/The-top-grossing-Christmas-films-of-all-time.html?frame=3136318|archive-date=June 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217210226/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt2709692/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|title=Dr. Seuss' The Grinch|last=|first=|date=|website=Box Office Mojo|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt2709692/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|archive-date=December 17, 2019|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> According to [[William Goldman]], the film's success prompted the creation of a Hollywood verb: \"to be ''Home Aloned''\", meaning to have a film's box office reduced by the impact of ''Home Alone''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Goldman |first=William |date=2001 |title=The Big Picture? Who Killed Hollywood and Other Essays |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Zt7TGNB8qyQC&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&q=%22to%20be%20home%20aloned%22 |publisher=Applause Theatre Books |page=49 |isbn=978-1557834607 |accessdate=January 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Home Alone'' holds an approval rating of 65% based on 54 reviews, with an average rating of 5.65/10. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''Home Alone''{{'}}s uneven but frequently funny premise stretched unreasonably thin is buoyed by Macaulay Culkin's cute performance and strong supporting stars.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712222710/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/home_alone/|title=Home Alone Movie Reviews|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/home_alone/|archive-date=June 12, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2017}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating, it has a score of 63 out of 100, based on 9 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205113241/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/home-alone|title=Home Alone Reviews|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/home-alone|archive-date=December 5, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= December 20, 2018 |access-date= July 24, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' magazine praised the film for its cast.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112143006/http://variety.com/1989/film/reviews/home-alone-1200428389/|title=Variety Reviews - Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117791714?refcatid=31|archive-date=November 12, 2013|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]}}</ref> Jeanne Cooper of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' praised the film for its comedic approach.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cooper|first=Jeanne|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406160806/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/homealonepgcooper_a09ecc.htm|title=Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/homealonepgcooper_a09ecc.htm|archive-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> Hal Hinson, also of ''The Washington Post'', praised Columbus' direction and Culkin's performance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hinson|first=Hal|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225112000/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/homealonepghinson_a0a9b9.htm|title=Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/homealonepghinson_a0a9b9.htm|archive-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> Although Caryn James of ''[[The New York Times]]'' complained that the film's first half is \"flat and unsurprising as its cute little premise suggests\", she praised the second half for its slapstick humor. She also praised the dialogue between Kevin and Marley, as well as the film's final scenes.<ref>{{cite news|last=James|first=Caryn|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417184530/https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/16/movies/review-film-holiday-black-comedy-for-modern-children.html|title=Movie Review - Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE6D8143DF935A25752C1A966958260|archive-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film a {{frac|2|1|2}} out of a 4-star rating and 2 thumbs down. He compared the elaborate booby-traps in the film to [[Rube Goldberg machine]]s, writing \"they're the kinds of traps that any 8-year-old could devise, if he had a budget of tens of thousands of dollars and the assistance of a crew of movie special effects people\" and criticized the plot as \"so implausible that it makes it hard for [him] to really care about the plight of the kid [Kevin]\". However, he praised Culkin's performance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20180918123627/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/home-alone-1990|title=Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19901116/REVIEWS/11160302|archive-date=August 18, 2019|authorlink=Roger Ebert}}</ref>\n\nOwen Gleiberman of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' magazine gave the film a \"D\" grade, criticizing the film for its \"sadistic festival of adult-bashing\". Gleiberman said that \"[John] Hughes is pulling our strings as though he'd never learn to do anything else\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190904145938/https://ew.com/article/2007/07/25/home-alone-2/|title=Home Alone|date=July 25, 2007|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318682,00.html|archive-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref> Peter Bradshaw of ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film 3 out of a 5-star rating and praised Culkin's \"vivid screen presence, almost incandescent with confidence.\" However, he criticised his acting, calling it \"a bit broad and mannered\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200407214024/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/nov/30/home-alone-review-yuletide-rerelease|title=Home Alone review \u2013 1990 Christmas cracker resurfaces|date=November 30, 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=February 21, 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/nov/30/home-alone-review-yuletide-rerelease|archive-date=April 7, 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Ali Barclay of the ''[[BBC Online|BBC]]'' wrote \"Culkin walks a fine line between annoyance and endearment throughout the film.\" He also called ''Home Alone'' \"a film which manages to capture some of the best qualities of Christmas\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190919113621/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/04/home_alone_1990_review.shtml|title=BBC - Films - review - Home Alone|last=Barclay|first=Ali|date=December 4, 2000|website=BBC|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/04/home_alone_1990_review.shtml|archive-date=September 19, 2019|access-date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNaomi Barnwell of ''Roobla'' said that \"''Home Alone'' has all the ingredients that make for a great kids\u2019 film\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://roobla.com/movies/1419/home-alone-1990/|title=Review: Home Alone (1990)|last=Barnwell|first=Naomi|date=December 13, 2010|website=Roobla|language=en-GB|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221203921/https://roobla.com/movies/1419/home-alone-1990/|archive-date=February 21, 2020|access-date=February 21, 2020}}</ref> Adrian Turner of Radio Times commented \"[Home Alone is] a celebration of enterprise that captured the heart and wickedness of every child on the planet.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228121514/https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cnmkh/home-alone/|title=Home Alone \u2013 review {{!}} cast and crew, movie star rating and where to watch film on TV and online|last=Turner|first=Adrian|date=|website=Radio Times|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cnmkh/home-alone/|archive-date=December 28, 2016|access-date=February 21, 2020}}</ref> According to [[TV Guide|''TV Guide'']], \"[''Home Alone'']'s slapstick falls flat and only the pain remains.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221203931/https://www.tvguide.com/movies/home-alone/review/128202/|title=Home Alone {{!}} TV Guide|last=|first=|date=|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/home-alone/review/128202|archive-date=February 21, 2020|access-date=February 21, 2020}}</ref> Marielle Sabbag of ''Vocal'' wrote \"Everything about [''Home Alone''] is beautiful and has a realistic quality.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222133119/https://vocal.media/geeks/home-alone-a-movie-review|title='Home Alone'\u2014A Movie Review|last=Sabbag|first=Marielle|date=|website=Geeks|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://vocal.media/geeks/home-alone-a-movie-review|archive-date=February 22, 2020|access-date=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Peter Rainer of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' criticised the fact that \"there is a reason why this film plays better as a trailer than as a full-length film.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222133123/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-11-16-ca-4515-story.html|title=MOVIE REVIEW : Kid Plays It for Laughs in 'Home Alone'|last=Rainer|first=Peter|date=November 16, 1990|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-11-16-ca-4515-story.html|archive-date=February 22, 2020|access-date=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the film's release, ''Home Alone'' gradually became a Christmas classic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715115846/https://www.joe.ie/movies-tv/10-reasons-why-home-alone-is-a-must-watch-during-the-christmas-season-478902|title=10 reasons why Home Alone will always be a Christmas classic|last=Moore|first=Paul|date=|website=JOE.ie|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.joe.ie/movies-tv/10-reasons-why-home-alone-is-a-must-watch-during-the-christmas-season-478902|archive-date=July 15, 2018|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412165419/https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/is-home-alone-the-best-christmas-movie-of-all-time/|title=Home Alone: the best Christmas movie of all time?|last=Clayton|first=James|date=November 16, 2019|website=Den of Geek|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/home-alone/33420/home-alone-the-best-christmas-movie-of-all-time|archive-date=April 12, 2020|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193249/https://archive.nerdist.com/home-alone-christmas-classic-breakdown/|title=What Makes HOME ALONE a Christmas Classic? \u2014 Nerdist|last=Walsh|first=Michael|date=December 8, 2017|website=Nerdist|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.nerdist.com/home-alone-christmas-classic-breakdown/|archive-date=February 23, 2020|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193250/https://www.vox.com/2015/11/16/9731584/home-alone-popular|title=Home Alone's enduring popularity, explained|last=Pai|first=Tanya|date=November 16, 2015|website=Vox|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.vox.com/2015/11/16/9731584/home-alone-popular|archive-date=February 23, 2020|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref> It was praised for its quotable phrases,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223194751/https://parade.com/955037/stefanieparker/home-alone-quotes/|title=Here Are the 31 Most Iconic Quotes From Home Alone\u2014Keep the Change, Ya Filthy Animal|last=Parker|first=Stefanie|date=November 19, 2019|website=Parade|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://parade.com/955037/stefanieparker/home-alone-quotes/|archive-date=February 23, 2020|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref> morals,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193249/https://www.theodysseyonline.com/home-alone-lessons-learned-|title=Lessons Learned From Watching Home Alone|last=|first=|date=January 9, 2019|website=The Odyssey Online|language=en-us|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/home-alone-lessons-learned-|archive-date=February 23, 2020|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref> traps,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bartleet|first=Larry|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193248/https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/kevin-mccallisters-25-cruellest-home-alone-traps-25-years-on-from-the-original-764578|title=Kevin McCallister's 25 cruellest Home Alone traps {{!}} NME|date=December 19, 2015|work=NME|access-date=February 23, 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/kevin-mccallisters-25-cruellest-home-alone-traps-25-years-on-from-the-original-764578|archive-date=February 23, 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> and main character.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193248/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/12/home-alone-is-basically-torture-porn/420471/|title='Home Alone': Beloved Holiday Torture Porn|last=Garber|first=Megan|date=December 15, 2015|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/12/home-alone-is-basically-torture-porn/420471/|archive-date=February 23, 2020|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref> Hannah-Rose Yee of [[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]] called the ending \"very sweet\" and praised the score from John Williams, calling it \"fantastic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410100425/https://www.stylist.co.uk/life/home-alone-review-macaulay-culkin-christmas-movie-classic-rewatch/334383|title=Home Alone: 19 thoughts I had watching the Christmas classic for the first time|last=Rose-Yee|first=Hannah|date=|website=Stylist|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.stylist.co.uk/life/home-alone-review-macaulay-culkin-christmas-movie-classic-rewatch/334383|archive-date=April 10, 2020|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Christopher Hooton of The Independent also praised the film, calling the film-within-a-film ''Angels with Filthy Souls'' \"a fond footnote in cinema history.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204105120/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/home-alone-cinemas-macaulay-culkin-john-hughes-behind-the-scenes-joe-pesci-john-candy-a8665336.html|title=Why Home Alone is back in cinemas, and why it won't leave our hearts|last=Hooton|first=Christopher|date=December 3, 2019|website=The Indepedent|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/home-alone-cinemas-macaulay-culkin-john-hughes-behind-the-scenes-joe-pesci-john-candy-a8665336.html|archive-date=December 4, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Matt Talbot from Simcoe.com said that the Wet Bandits were \"fantastic\" and \"never [got] old\" on \"repeat viewings.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307220106/https://www.simcoe.com/whatson-story/2052295-movie-review-home-alone/|title=MOVIE REVIEW: Home Alone|last=Talbot|first=Matt|date=December 17, 2012|website=Simcoe.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.simcoe.com/whatson-story/2052295-movie-review-home-alone/|archive-date=March 7, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Michael Walsh of Nerdist noted the church scene as \"One of the best, most touching scenes [in the film]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223193249/https://archive.nerdist.com/home-alone-christmas-classic-breakdown/|title=What Makes HOME ALONE a Christmas Classic?|last=Walsh|first=Michael|date=December 8, 2017|website=Nerdist|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.nerdist.com/home-alone-christmas-classic-breakdown/|archive-date=February 23, 2020|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nAt the [[12th Youth in Film Awards]], Macaulay Culkin won Best Young Actor Starring in a Motion Picture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms12.htm|title=Twelfth Annual Youth in Film Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=YoungArtistAwards.org|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707191726/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms12.htm|archive-date=July 7, 2011|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref> The film was nominated for two [[Academy Award]]s, one for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], which was written by [[John Williams]], and the other for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"Somewhere in My Memory\", music by Williams and lyrics by [[Leslie Bricusse]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1354610533731 |title=Home Alone search |work=The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |accessdate=December 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130415161322/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1354610533731 |archivedate=April 15, 2013  }}</ref>\n\n===Accusations of plagiarism===\nThe 1989 [[Cinema of France|French film]] ''[[3615 code P\u00e8re No\u00ebl]]'', which is about a young boy who is home alone with his elderly grandfather and has to fend off a home invader dressed up as [[Santa Claus]], has been noted for its plot similarities to ''Home Alone''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418032406/https://www.20minutes.fr/culture/1756103-20151224-video-pere-noel-mode-trash|title=Le p\u00e8re No\u00ebl en mode trash|last=Demoulin|first=Anne|date=December 24, 2015|website=20minutes.fr|publisher=[[20 minutes (France)|20 minutes]]|language=fr|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.20minutes.fr/culture/1756103-20151224-video-pere-noel-mode-trash|archive-date=April 18, 2019|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref> ''3615 code P\u00e8re No\u00ebl'' director Ren\u00e9 Manzor threatened the makers of ''Home Alone'' with legal action on the grounds of plagiarism, alleging that ''Home Alone'' was a remake of his film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412171138/https://www.vanityfair.fr/culture/ecrans/articles/ces-choses-que-vous-ignorez-encore-sur-maman-jai-rate-lavion-/48735|title=14 choses que vous ignorez encore sur ''Maman, j'ai rat\u00e9 l'avion''|last=Vanwetswinkel|first=Margaux|date=December 15, 2016|website=vanityfair.fr|publisher=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|language=fr|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.vanityfair.fr/culture/cinema/articles/ces-choses-que-vous-ignorez-encore-sur-maman-jai-rate-lavion-/48735|archive-date=April 12, 2020|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124074001/https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/15/movies/film-hollywood-law-whose-idea-is-it-anyway.html?pagewanted=2|title=Hollywood Law: Whose Idea Is It, Anyway?|last=Horowitz|first=Joy|date=March 15, 1992|website=nytimes.com|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/15/movies/film-hollywood-law-whose-idea-is-it-anyway.html?pagewanted=2|archive-date=January 24, 2020|accessdate=December 23, 2016}}</ref> ''3615 code P\u00e8re No\u00ebl'' was not released in the United States during its original theatrical run in January 1990 and did not become widely available there until 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131194718/https://www.americangenrefilm.com/theatrical-film-catalog/dial-code-santa-claus-aka-deadly-games/|title=American Genre Film Archive DIAL CODE SANTA CLAUS|last=|first=|date=|website=www.americangenrefilm.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.americangenrefilm.com/theatrical-film-catalog/dial-code-santa-claus-aka-deadly-games/|archive-date=January 31, 2020|access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Franchise==\n{{main|Home Alone (franchise)}}\n===Sequels===\nThe film was followed by a commercially successful sequel in 1992, ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York|Lost in New York]]'', which brought back most of the first film's cast. Culkin was paid $4.5 million to appear in the sequel, compared to $110,000 for the original.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211152658/https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/59269|title=AFI{{!}}Catalog - Home Alone 2: Lost in New York|last=|first=|date=|website=catalog.afi.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/59269|archive-date=February 11, 2020|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> The film within a film, ''Angels with Filthy Souls'', had a sequel in ''Home Alone 2'', ''Angels with Even Filthier Souls''. Both ''Angels'' meta-films featured character actor [[Ralph Foody]] as stereotypical 1930s mobster Johnny.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205025718/https://thefw.com/things-you-didnt-know-about-home-alone/|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About 'Home Alone'|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=The FW|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://thefw.com/things-you-didnt-know-about-home-alone/|archive-date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Home Alone 3]]'' was released in 1997; it has entirely different actors and characters as well as a different storyline, with Hughes writing the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404100501/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/home-alone-3-1997|title=Home Alone 3 movie review & film summary (1997) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/home-alone-3-1997|archive-date=April 4, 2020|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA fourth [[Made for TV film|made-for-TV film]] followed in 2002, ''[[Home Alone 4|Home Alone 4: Taking Back the House]]''. The movie features some of the same characters who were in the first two films, but with a new cast and a storyline that does not fall into the same continuity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222003218/https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cw9z5/home-alone-4/|title=Home Alone 4 \u2013 review {{!}} cast and crew, movie star rating and where to watch film on TV and online|last=|first=|date=|website=Radio Times|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cw9z5/home-alone-4/|archive-date=December 22, 2019|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref> On November 25, 2012, a fifth film, ''[[Home Alone: The Holiday Heist|The Holiday Heist]],'' premiered during [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] Family's Countdown to [[25 Days of Christmas]] programming event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/10/05/abc-family-presents-countdown-to-25-days-of-christmas-starting-sunday-november-18/151780/|title=ABC Family Presents 'Countdown to 25 Days of Christmas' Starting Sunday, November 18|last=Bibel|first=Sara|date=October 5, 2012|website=TV by the Numbers|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014134337/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/10/05/abc-family-presents-countdown-to-25-days-of-christmas-starting-sunday-november-18/151780/|archive-date=October 14, 2012|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref> Similarly to the third film, it does not focus on the McCallister family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202124527/http://terriblemoviesforterriblepeople.com/2014/12/home-alone-the-holiday-heist-2012.html|title=Home Alone the Holiday Heist \u2013 2012|last=|first=|date=December 8, 2014|website=Terrible Movies For Terrible People|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://terriblemoviesforterriblepeople.com/2014/12/home-alone-the-holiday-heist-2012.html|archive-date=February 2, 2020|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n===Reboot===\nOn August 6, 2019, [[Disney]] announced plans to reboot the franchise on its [[Disney+]] [[Streaming media|streaming service]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309095853/https://deadline.com/2019/08/disney-plus-home-alone-night-at-the-museum-reboots-fox-1202662998/|title=Disney+ To Revive 'Home Alone'|author=Hayes|first=Dade|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|date=August 6, 2019|website=Deadline|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/disney-plus-home-alone-night-at-the-museum-reboots-fox-1202662998/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref> On December 10, 2019, [[Archie Yates]], [[Ellie Kemper]], and [[Rob Delaney]] were announced as the cast for a reboot. Yates will not play Kevin, and will have a new story. The story reportedly \"sees Kemper and Delaney play a wife and husband who, in order to save their home from financial ruin, go to war with a kid who has stolen a priceless heirloom.\" [[Dan Mazer]] will direct, from a script by [[Mikey Day]] and [[Streeter Seidell]], and produced by Hutch Parker and Dan Wilson. The film will be a production of [[20th Century Fox]], and marks the first Fox produced project on Disney+. It is set to film in early 2020 in Canada.<ref name=\"archiereboot\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105154032/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jojo-rabbit-breakout-archie-yates-lead-home-alone-reboot-1261606|title='Jojo Rabbit' Breakout Archie Yates to Lead \u2018Home Alone\u2019 Reboot|last1=Galuppo|first1=Mia|date=|website=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jojo-rabbit-breakout-archie-yates-lead-home-alone-reboot-1261606|archive-date=January 5, 2020|accessdate=December 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"rebootcast\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409064558/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/home-alone-reboot-archie-yates-ellie-kemper-rob-delaney-1203432212/|title=\u2018Home Alone\u2019 Reboot Taps \u2018Jojo Rabbit\u2019s\u2019 Archie Yates, Ellie Kemper, Rob Delaney (EXCLUSIVE)|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|date=|website=Variety|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/home-alone-reboot-archie-yates-ellie-kemper-rob-delaney-1203432212/|archive-date=April 9, 2020|accessdate=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Homages==\nThe music video for [[Snoop Dogg]]'s 1994 single \"[[Gin and Juice]]\" opens with a gag where, after a teenaged Snoop's parents have left him to watch the house in their absence, he places his hands to his face and yells in the manner of Kevin McCallister in the first film, while a title comes on screen reading \"Home Boy Alone.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202101636/https://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/18468/1/gin-and-juice-turns-20-gettin-loose-for-a-good-reason|title=Gin and Juice turns 20: Gettin' loose for a good reason|last=Dazed|first=|date=January 16, 2014|website=Dazed|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/18468/1/gin-and-juice-turns-20-gettin-loose-for-a-good-reason|archive-date=February 2, 2020|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Culkin reprised his role as an adult Kevin McCallister in the inaugural episode of the [[Jack Dishel]] web series, \"DRYVRS\", where a visibly disturbed Kevin recounts his experience of being left home alone by his family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531074926/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/see-macaulay-culkin-revisit-traumatized-home-alone-character-55069/|title=See Macaulay Culkin Revisit Traumatized 'Home Alone' Character|author=Ehrlich|first=David|date=December 17, 2015|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/videos/see-macaulay-culkin-revisit-traumatized-home-alone-character-20151217|archive-date=May 31, 2019|accessdate=December 18, 2015}}</ref> In response to Culkin's video, Daniel Stern appeared in a short video reprising his role as Marv, released in conjunction with Stern's [[Reddit#IAmA and AMA|Reddit AMA]], where he pleads for Harry to return to help protect him against Kevin's traps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190827164938/https://people.com/celebrity/the-wet-bandits-are-back-daniel-stern-releases-a-video-response-to-macaulay-culkins-home-alone-parody/|title=The Wet Bandits Are Back! Daniel Stern Releases a Video Response to Macaulay Culkin's Home Alone Parody|author=Pearl|first=Diana|date=December 26, 2015|work=People Magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.people.com/article/daniel-stern-video-response-macaulay-culkin-home-alone-video|archive-date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=December 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 2016 Christmas-set horror film ''[[Better Watch Out]]'' includes a scene where a character who is obsessed with the ''Home Alone'' films demonstrates how, in real life, it would be deadly for someone to be hit in the face with a paint can swung from a distance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200407230205/https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3597558/revisiting-better-watch-memorable-home-alone-inspired-kill/|title=Revisiting \u2018Better Watch Out\u2019 and Its Memorable \u2018Home Alone\u2019 Inspired Kill!|last=Navarro|first=Meagan|date=December 18, 2019|website=Bloody Disgusting!|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3597558/revisiting-better-watch-memorable-home-alone-inspired-kill/|archive-date=April 7, 2020|access-date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn December 15, 2018, Culkin made a guest appearance as himself in an episode of ''[[Angry Video Game Nerd|The Angry Video Game Nerd]]'' to review multiple video game adaptations of the first two ''Home Alone'' films, as well as a gameplay session of [[The Pagemaster (video game)|''The Pagemaster'']] with [[James Rolfe]] and [[Mike Matei]] in the days following that episode's release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190804153639/https://www.polygon.com/2018/12/16/18143355/angry-video-game-nerd-macaulay-culkin-home-alone-video-games|title=Macaulay Culkin teams with Angry Video Game Nerd to dump on Home Alone|last1=Good|first1=Owen S.|date=December 16, 2018|website=Polygon|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/12/16/18143355/angry-video-game-nerd-macaulay-culkin-home-alone-video-games|archive-date=August 4, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 19, 2018, Culkin would once again reprise his role as an adult Kevin McCallister in a 60 second advertisement for [[Google Assistant]], titled ''Home Alone Again.'' The commercial contains [[Shot-for-shot|shot for shot remakes]] of scenes from the film. Google Assistant helps Kevin set up the house to look active by remotely turning on lights, devices, and setting up cutouts of people, in order to have the thieves parked in a van outside (presumably Harry and Marv) steer clear of the house.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Parker|first1=Ryan|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190327091419/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/macaulay-culkin-creates-home-alone-scenes-google-assistant-ad-1170770|title=Macaulay Culkin Re-Creates 'Home Alone' Scenes for Google Assistant Ad|date=December 19, 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 21, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/macaulay-culkin-creates-home-alone-scenes-google-assistant-ad-1170770|archive-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, Joe Pesci also reprised his role as Harry, only for his voice making a small cameo. Pesci later appeared in another ad where he watches the short with his friends and jokes about his brief cameo.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Scott|first=Ryan|date=February 1, 2019|title=Joe Pesci returns in new Home Alone Google commercial|url=https://movieweb.com/home-alone-joe-pesci-google-assistant-commercial/|work=[[MovieWeb]]|accessdate=February 3, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202034213/https://movieweb.com/home-alone-joe-pesci-google-assistant-commercial/|archivedate=February 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Novelization==\n''Home Alone'' ({{ISBN|0-590-55066-7}}) was novelized by [[Todd Strasser]] and published by [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]] in 1990 to coincide with the film.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Home_Alone.html?id=D4FSjlUEIGsC&redir_esc=y|title=Home Alone|last=Strasser|first=Todd|date=1990|publisher=Scholastic|isbn=978-0-590-44668-6|language=en}}</ref> On October 6, 2015, to celebrate the 25th anniversary of the movie, an illustrated book by Kim Smith and [[Quirk Books]] was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20171129225735/https://www.buzzfeed.com/krystieyandoli/i-made-my-family-disappear?utm_term=.xejxR8eZx|title=This Illustrated \"Home Alone\" Storybook Will Make You So Excited For Christmas|last=Yandoli|first=Krystie Lee|date=November 9, 2015|website=|publisher=BuzzFeed|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/krystieyandoli/i-made-my-family-disappear|archive-date=November 29, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Home Alone: The Classic Illustrated Storybook |publisher=Quirk Books |isbn=1594748586}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1990]]\n* [[List of films featuring home invasions]], a plot device in thriller films that ''Home Alone'' lampoons<ref>{{cite news|last=Sragow|first=Michael|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20191223202450/https://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/bs-xpm-2010-12-23-bs-ae-sragow-rail-1224-20101223-story.html|title='Home Alone' is the Charles' post-Christmas gift for kids, parents and hipsters|date=December 23, 2010|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|access-date=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/bs-xpm-2010-12-23-bs-ae-sragow-rail-1224-20101223-story.html|archive-date=December 23, 2019|quote=For one sequence, the movie becomes a cat-and-mouse cartoon and a lampoon of home-invasion thrillers.}}</ref>\n* [[List of films featuring fictional films]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote|Home Alone}}\n* {{IMDb title|0099785|Home Alone}}\n* {{tcmdb title|36532|Home Alone}}\n* {{Mojo title|homealone|Home Alone}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|home_alone}}\n* {{Metacritic film|home-alone|Home Alone}}\n* [http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1990/0HMLN.php ''Home Alone''] at The Numbers\n\n{{Portal bar|United States|Film|1990s}}\n{{Home Alone}}\n{{Chris Columbus}}\n{{John Hughes}}\n\n[[Category:Home Alone (franchise)]]\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990s Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:American children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:American crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Burglary in film]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Chris Columbus]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films produced by John Hughes (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Williams]]\n[[Category:Films set in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by John Hughes (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:Home invasions in film]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1990 film directed by Chris Columbus}} \n{{About|the first film in the series|the series|Home Alone (franchise)|other uses|Home Alone (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2019}}{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Home Alone\n| image          = Home alone poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]]\n| producer       = [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]]\n| writer         = John Hughes\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|<!-- Per [[Template:Infobox film]], only the actors on the film's billing block should be listed. -->\n* [[Macaulay Culkin]]\n* [[Joe Pesci]]\n* [[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]]\n* [[John Heard (actor)|John Heard]]\n* [[Catherine O'Hara]]\n}}\n| music          = [[John Williams]]\n| cinematography = [[Julio Macat]]\n| editing        = [[Raja Gosnell]]\n| studio         = Hughes Entertainment\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1990|11|10|Chicago|1990|11|16|United States}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 102:36--><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227075147/https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/home-alone-1970-3|title=HOME ALONE (PG)|last=|first=|date=|website=British Board of Film Classification|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/home-alone-1970-3|archive-date=February 27, 2020|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $18 million<ref name=mojo>{{cite web |title = Home Alone (1990) |url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200211151647/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3629745665/weekend/ |archive-url = http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=homealone.htm |website = [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate = November 19, 2011 |archive-date = 2020-02-23}}</ref>\n| gross          = $476.7 million<ref name=mojo />\n}}\n\n'''''Home Alone''''' is a 1990 American [[comedy film]] written and produced by [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]] and directed by [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]]. It stars [[Macaulay Culkin]], [[Joe Pesci]], [[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]], [[John Heard (actor)|John Heard]], and [[Catherine O'Hara]]. The film follows an eight-year-old boy (Culkin), who must defend his home from two burglars (Pesci and Stern) after his family mistakenly leaves him behind on their Christmas vacation. It was filmed between February and May of 1990, in an array of locations. The film was originally meant to be a production from [[Warner Bros.]], but was changed to a [[20th Century Fox]] production when Hughes exceeded a $10 million budget that he promised for the film with Warner Bros. \n\n''Home Alone'' premiered on November 10, 1990, in Chicago, and was released wider in the United States on November 16, 1990. With a total gross of $476.7 million, it was the highest-grossing live-action comedy ever, and held the record until it was overtaken by ''[[The Hangover Part II]]'' in 2011. The film received two [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor in a Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] for Culkin, as well as two [[Academy Award]] nominations for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], which was composed by [[John Williams]], and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"Somewhere in My Memory\". Despite receiving mixed reviews from critics on its initial release, ''Home Alone'' has been hailed as a holiday classic among audiences and is often regarded as one of the best Christmas films ever made.\n\n''Home Alone'' spawned a successful [[Home Alone (franchise)|film franchise]] that started with the 1992 sequel ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York]]'', which is the only ''Home Alone'' sequel to have most of the original cast reprising their roles.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- NOTICE: Plot summaries should be 400-700 words. See WP:FILMPLOT. Do not add unnecessary detail to this section. -->\nThe McCallister family is preparing to spend Christmas in Paris, gathering at Peter and Kate's home in a [[Chicago]] [[Chicago land|suburb]] on the night before their departure. Peter and Kate's youngest son, Kevin, is the subject of ridicule by his older siblings. Later, Kevin accidentally ruins the family dinner and their flight tickets to Paris after a scuffle with his older brother Buzz, resulting in him getting sent to the [[attic]] of the house as a punishment, where he berates Kate and wishes that his family would disappear. During the night, heavy winds damage the power lines, which causes a [[power outage]] and resets the alarm clocks, causing the family to oversleep. In the confusion and rush to get to the airport, Kevin is accidentally left behind.\n\nKevin wakes to find the house empty and, thinking that his wish has come true, is overjoyed with his newfound freedom. However, he soon becomes frightened by his next door neighbor, Old Man Marley, who is rumored to be a [[serial killer]] who murdered his own family, as well as the \"Wet Bandits\", Harry and Marv, a pair of burglars who have been breaking into other vacant houses in the neighborhood and have targeted the McCallisters' house. Kevin tricks them into thinking that his family is still home, forcing them to put their plans on hold.\n\nKate realizes mid-flight that Kevin was left behind, and upon arrival in Paris, the family discovers that all flights for the next two days are booked. Peter and the rest of the family stay in his brother's apartment in Paris, while Kate manages to get a flight back to the United States, but only gets as far as [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]. She attempts to book a flight to Chicago, but again, everything is booked. Unable to accept this, Kate is overheard by Gus Polinski, the lead member of a traveling polka band, who offers to let her travel with them to [[Chicago]] on their way to [[Milwaukee]] in a moving van, which she gratefully accepts.\n\nMeanwhile, Harry and Marv finally realize that Kevin is home alone, and on Christmas Eve, Kevin overhears them discussing plans to break into his house that night. Kevin starts to miss his family and asks the local [[Santa Claus]] impersonator if he could bring his family back for Christmas. He goes to church and watches a [[choir]] perform, then meets Old Man Marley, who dispels the rumors about him. He points out his granddaughter in the choir, whom he never gets to meet, as he and his son are estranged; Kevin suggests that he should reconcile with his son.\n\nKevin returns home and rigs the house with [[booby trap]]s to take on the burglars. Harry and Marv break in, spring the traps, and suffer various injuries. While the duo pursues Kevin around the house, he calls the police and flees, then lures Harry and Marv into a neighboring home which they previously broke into. They ambush him and prepare to get their revenge, but Marley intervenes and knocks them unconscious with his snow shovel. The police arrive and arrest Harry and Marv, having identified all the houses that they broke into due to Marv's destructive characteristic of flooding them.\n\nOn Christmas Day, Kevin is disappointed to find that his family is still gone. He then hears Kate enter the house and call for him; they reconcile and are soon joined by Peter, Buzz, Jeff, Megan, and Linnie, who waited in Paris until they could obtain a direct flight to Chicago. Kevin keeps silent about his encounter with Harry and Marv, although Peter finds Harry's knocked-out gold tooth. Kevin then observes Marley reuniting with his son, daughter-in-law, and granddaughter. Marley notices Kevin, and the pair wave to each other.\n\n==Cast==\n<!--ACCORDING TO THE END CREDITS OF THE FILM per WP:FILMCAST-->\n{{cast list|\n* [[Macaulay Culkin]] as Kevin, a rambunctious eight-year-old with a penchant for creating harmful inventions\n* [[Joe Pesci]] as Harry, a short and hotheaded thief who targets the McCallisters' home with Marv\n* [[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]] as Marv, a tall and dim-witted thief who targets the McCallisters' home with Harry\n* [[John Heard (actor)|John Heard]] as Peter, Kevin's father\n* [[Roberts Blossom]] as Marley, Kevin's elderly neighbor\n* [[Catherine O'Hara]] as Kate, Kevin's mother and Peter's wife\n* [[Angela Goethals]] as Linnie, Kevin's older sister\n* [[Devin Ratray]] as Buzz, Kevin's oldest brother who often gets him into trouble\n* [[Gerry Bamman]] as Uncle Frank, Peter's older brother\n* [[Hillary Wolf]] as Megan, Kevin's oldest sister\n* [[John Candy]] as Gus Polinski, polka performer who helps Kate\n* [[Larry Hankin]] as Officer Balzak\n* [[Michael C. Maronna]] as Jeff, Kevin's older brother\n* [[Kristin Minter]] as Heather, Kevin's oldest cousin\n* Daiana Campeanu as Sondra, Kevin's older cousin\n* Jedidiah Cohen as Rod, Kevin's older cousin\n* [[Kieran Culkin]] as Fuller, Kevin's youngest cousin\n* [[Senta Moses]] as Tracy, Kevin's older cousin\n* [[Anna Slotky]] as Brook, Kevin's younger cousin\n* Terrie Snell as Aunt Leslie, Uncle Frank's wife\n* Jeffrey Wiseman as Mitch Murphy, 8-year-old neighbor whom Heather mistakes for Kevin during the headcount\n* Virginia Smith as Georgette, Kevin's aunt, wife of Uncle Rob, and mother of Heather and Steffan\n* [[Matt Doherty (actor)|Matt Doherty]] as Steffan, Kevin's older cousin\n* [[Ralph Foody]] as Gangster #1 (Johnny), character in the film ''Angels with Filthy Souls''\n* Michael Guido as Gangster #2 (Snakes), character in the film ''Angels with Filthy Souls''\n* Ray Toler as Uncle Rob, Kevin's uncle, younger brother of Peter and Uncle Frank, and father of Heather and Steffan\n* [[Billie Bird]] as Woman in Airport, Irene, who sells Kate her ticket to Dallas\n* [[Bill Erwin]] as Man in Airport, Ed, Irene's husband who agrees with Irene's ticket sale\n* [[Gerry Becker]] as Officer #1\n* [[Alan Wilder (actor)|Alan Wilder]] as Scranton Ticket Agent\n* [[Hope Davis]] as French Ticket Agent\n* [[Kenneth Hudson Campbell]] as Santa, Santa Claus impersonator seen by Kevin\n}}\nCredits adapted from Rotten Tomatoes.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\" />\n==Production==\n===Development===\nThe conception of ''Home Alone'' arose from a personal dilemma that producer John Hughes had faced. Hughes explained that \"I was going away on vacation, and making a list of everything I didn\u2019t want to forget. I thought, 'well, I'd better not forget my kids.' Then I thought, 'what if I left my 10-year-old son at home? What would he do?{{Single+double}}<ref name=\"conception\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190519015208/http://time.com/4105161/home-alone-1990/|title=How John Hughes Came Up With Home Alone|last=|first=|date=November 16, 2015|website=Time|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://time.com/4105161/home-alone-1990/|archive-date=2019-05-19|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Hughes then wrote eight pages of notes that developed into the screenplay of the film.<ref name=conception/> Imagining that children are naturally most scared of robbers, Hughes also worked that aspect into the plot of the film.<ref name=conception/>\n\n''Home Alone'' was initially a [[Warner Bros.]] production. Hughes had promised the studio he could make the movie for no more than $10 million, considerably less than most feature film production budgets of that era. Concerned that the film might exceed that amount, even minimally, and that Warner would insist on keeping to it, Hughes met secretly with [[20th Century Fox]] before production to see if they would be interested in funding the project if Warner proved as inflexible as the producer feared. A copy of the script was \"clandestinely\" delivered to Fox, according to [[executive producer]] Scott Rosenfelt, bypassing the legal restrictions that would have otherwise prevented Fox from seeing it until the project was in [[Turnaround (filmmaking)|turnaround]].<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\">{{cite news|last=Bucklow|first=Andrew|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212233609/https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/home-alone-secrets-revealed-in-netflix-show-the-movies-that-made-us/news-story/7dd4896680c9c157e18b7f4e264c418f|title=''Home Alone'' secrets revealed in Netflix show 'The Movies That Made Us'|date=December 4, 2019|newspaper=[[news.com.au]]|accessdate=December 4, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/home-alone-secrets-revealed-in-netflix-show-the-movies-that-made-us/news-story/7dd4896680c9c157e18b7f4e264c418f|archive-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nEarly in production, the film's budget grew to $14.7 million, well past the limit Warner had imposed. The studio demanded that it be cut by $1.2 million; the producers responded with a memo arguing that the budget could not be cut any further. Warner, unconvinced, shut down production the next day. It quickly resumed as Fox took up Hughes on his earlier offer. The final budget would grow to $18 million.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" />\n\nHughes had originally asked [[Patrick Read Johnson]] to direct, but he was already committed to ''[[Spaced Invaders]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=John Hughes: A Life in Film|last=Honeycutt|first=Kirk|publisher=Race Point Publishing|year=2015|isbn=978-1631060229|location=|pages=}}</ref> He then turned to Chris Columbus, who had left ''[[National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation]]'' before shooting started, because of a personality clash with starring actor [[Chevy Chase]], who Columbus said treated him \"like dirt\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406032958/https://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/December-2015/Home-Alone/|title=Holy Cow, Home Alone Is 25!|last=|first=|date=November 10, 2015|website=|publisher=chicagomag.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/December-2015/Home-Alone/|archive-date=2020-04-06|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Hughes then gave him the script for both ''Home Alone'' and ''[[Reach the Rock]]''; Columbus accepted the former, as he found it funnier and liked the Christmas theme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219083024/https://www.vulture.com/2015/11/columbus-directed-home-alone-because-chevy-chase.html|title=Chris Columbus Directed Home Alone Instead of Christmas Vacation Because He Met Chevy Chase|last1=Madison III|first1=Ira|date=2015-11-10|website=Vulture|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/11/columbus-directed-home-alone-because-chevy-chase.html|archive-date=2019-12-19|accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"EW2016\" /> Columbus became the director of the film.<ref name=\"EW2016\" />\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Macaulay Culkin 1991 B.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Macaulay Culkin]] (pictured in 1991), was the child star of the film.]]\nHughes suggested to Columbus that they cast [[Macaulay Culkin]] in the main role, because of his experience with the child actor while shooting ''[[Uncle Buck]]''. Columbus met with other actors for the part, by his count \"hundreds and hundreds\" (actually 200), as he felt it was his \"directorial presponsibility\".<ref name=\"EW2016\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229151131/https://ew.com/article/2015/11/06/home-alone-turns-25-chris-columbus/|title=Home Alone turns 25: A deep dive with director Chris Columbus|last1=Wilkinson|first1=Amy|date=2015-11-06|website=Entertainment Weekly|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/11/06/home-alone-turns-25-chris-columbus|archive-date=2019-12-29|accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Columbus finally met with Culkin and agreed he was the right choice for the role.<ref name=EW2016/> \n\nFor the role of Harry, one of the bandits, [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Jon Lovitz]] were considered for the role. After both rejected it, [[Joe Pesci]] accepted it.<ref name=\":2\" /> The role of Uncle Frank was originally written for [[Kelsey Grammer]], but given to [[Gerry Bamman]] when Grammer was unavailable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221155545/https://www.glamour.com/story/15-facts-about-home-alone|title=15 Fascinating Facts You Never Knew About Home Alone|last=Eidell|first=Lynsey|date=2015-11-16|website=Glamour|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.glamour.com/story/15-facts-about-home-alone|archive-date=2020-02-21|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221155549/https://www.looper.com/33705/cast-home-alone-today/|title=Where the cast of Home Alone is today|last=Moore|first=Trent|date=2017-07-22|website=Looper.com|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.looper.com/33705/cast-home-alone-today/|archive-date=2020-02-21|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n[[Daniel Stern (actor)|Daniel Stern]] was cast as Marv, but before shooting started, he was told that the production schedule had been extended from six weeks to eight. He was told there was no money in the budget for a pay increase he sought, so he quit. [[Daniel Roebuck]] was quickly hired to replace him, but after two days of rehearsal, Columbus did not see any chemistry between him and Pesci and decided to bring back Stern.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" /> Roebuck later admitted that, although he was upset to be fired from the production, he now believes the experience to be \"such a little blip of unimportance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204183429/https://mediamikes.com/2010/06/interview-with-daniel-roebuck/|title=Interview with Daniel Roebuck|last=Gencarelli|first=Mike|date=June 9, 2010|website=MediaMikes|publisher=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://mediamikes.com/2010/06/interview-with-daniel-roebuck/|archive-date=2019-12-04|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n[[John Candy]] had only one day to film his scenes; it took 23 hours. He was paid $414, since he did the film as a favor to Hughes. In return, he was the only actor Hughes allowed to go off-script {{En dash}} according to Columbus, all his dialogue was improvised.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" />\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Home Alone House.jpg|thumb|The ''Home Alone'' house in [[Winnetka, Illinois]].|alt=|left]]\n[[Principal photography]] took place between February and May 1990.<ref>Weekly Variety Magazine; February 14, 1990; Page 28</ref><ref>Daily Variety Magazine; May 8, 1990; Page 18</ref> Some scenes were shot in a three-story single-family house located at 671 Lincoln Avenue<ref name= \"sold2012\">{{cite web| title= ''Home Alone'' House Sells For $1.585 Million| url= http://www.chicagonow.com/getting-real/2012/03/home-alone-house-sells-for-1-585-million/ | date= March 9, 2012 | first=Gary|last= Lucido| work= Chicago Tribune | accessdate=March 11, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310170239/http://www.chicagonow.com/getting-real/2012/03/home-alone-house-sells-for-1-585-million/|archive-date=March 10, 2012}}</ref> in the [[North Shore (Chicago)|North Shore]] village of [[Winnetka, Illinois|Winnetka]], where Hughes's previous films ''[[The Breakfast Club|Breakfast Club]]'',  ''[[Ferris Bueller's Day Off]]'', ''[[Sixteen Candles]]'', ''[[Planes, Trains & Automobiles]]'', ''[[She's Having a Baby]]'', and ''[[Uncle Buck]]'' had also been shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522193126/http://movie-locations.com/movies/h/Home-Alone.php|title=Home Alone filming locations|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=movie-locations.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/h/homealone.html|archive-date=2019-05-22|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> The kitchen in the film was [[location filming|shot on location]], along with the main staircase, basement, attic and most of the first floor landing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movielocationsguide.com/Home_Alone_2:_Lost_in_New_York/filming_locations|title=Home Alone 2: Lost in New York Filming Locations|accessdate=June 15, 2008|publisher=movielocationsguide.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117153723/http://www.movielocationsguide.com/Home_Alone_2:_Lost_in_New_York/filming_locations|archive-date=November 17, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The tree house in the back yard was built specifically for the film and dismantled after filming ended.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite magazine|last=Wood|first=Jennifer|date=November 16, 2015|title=25 Things You Might Not Know About Home Alone|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406160806/https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/60262/25-things-you-might-not-know-about-home-alone|magazine=Mental Floss|page=|pages=|doi=|pmid=|archive-url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/60262/25-things-you-might-not-know-about-home-alone|archive-date=2020-04-06|accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref> All the other interiors were duplicated on a [[soundstage]] to allow more room for equipment and crew. It was built in the gym and empty swimming pool of the former [[New Trier High School]] building, previously used by Hughes for ''Uncle Buck'' and ''Ferris Bueller's Day Off'', where the production company had already set up its offices.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" /> The scenes inside the church were shot at Grace Episcopal Church in [[Oak Park, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Weddings at Grace|website=Grace Oak Park |url=https://www.graceoakpark.org/Weddings_at_Grace.html|url-status=dead|archivedate=May 8, 2016|df=mdy-all|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508234005/https://www.graceoakpark.org/Weddings_at_Grace.html}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Angels with Filthy Souls}}For the [[Story within a story#Film within a film|film within a film]], ''Angels with Filthy Souls'' (a parody of the 1938 crime film ''[[Angels with Dirty Faces]]''), shooting took only one day. To create the illusion that the film was a 1940s [[mob film|gangster film]], the scene was filmed with black-and-white negative film and Johnny's office used authentic items from that era.<ref name=\"Vanity Fair\">{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Darryn|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113105148/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/12/home-alone-gangster-movie|title=\"Merry Christmas, Ya Filthy Animal\": Inside the Making of Home Alone's Fake Gangster Movie|date=22 December 2015|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=20 November 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/12/home-alone-gangster-movie|archive-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n\nCinematographer [[Julio Macat]] recalled that Pesci was more difficult to work with than Culkin. The older actor believed some of the dialogue was not of a quality commensurate with his acting ability. He also resented the early unit calls, since they prevented him from starting his day with nine holes of golf as he preferred to do.<ref name=\"The Movies that Made Us\" /> After he took the [[assistant director]] by the collar one day to complain about this, daily call times were moved back from 7 to 9 a.m. to accommodate his rounds.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reilly|first=Tim|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206125647/https://www.golf.com/news/2019/12/02/joe-pesci-demanded-call-time-change-to-play-golf-while-filming-home-alone/|title=Joe Pesci demanded call time change to play golf while filming Home Alone|date=December 2, 2019|newspaper=[[Golf (magazine)|Golf]]|accessdate=December 4, 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.golf.com/news/2019/12/02/joe-pesci-demanded-call-time-change-to-play-golf-while-filming-home-alone/|archive-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> On the other end of the schedule, the crew had limited time to film the many nighttime scenes, since Culkin could not work any later than 10 p.m. due to his age.<ref name=EW2016/>\n\nOn the set, Pesci and Stern both had difficulty refraining from swear words, which became annoying to Pesci, since Culkin was on set as well. In fact, the only swear word that made it into the film was \"shit\", accidentally said by Daniel Stern when his shoe fell through the doggy door.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Snopek|first=Amy|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406160808/https://www.buzzfeed.com/amysno/17-things-you-didnt-know-about-home-alone-gk57|title=17 Things You Didn't Know About \"Home Alone\"|date=2013-11-15|work=BuzzFeed|access-date=2018-04-05|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/amysno/17-things-you-didnt-know-about-home-alone-gk57|archive-date=2020-04-06|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614162658/https://www.buzzfeed.com/terripous/youre-what-the-french-like-to-call-les-incompetent|title=24 Things You Probably Didn't Know About \"Home Alone\"|last=Pous|first=Terri|date=2016-12-04|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/terripous/youre-what-the-french-like-to-call-les-incompetent|archive-date=2019-06-14|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref> Pesci's use of \"cartoon cursing\", or menacing gibberish, garnered comparisons to ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' character [[Yosemite Sam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/archives/where-joe-pesci-saw-a-connection-between-looney-tunes-and-home-alone-1.4940775|title=Where Joe Pesci saw a connection between Looney Tunes and Home Alone|publisher=cbc.ca|date=December 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211185216/https://www.cbc.ca/archives/where-joe-pesci-saw-a-connection-between-looney-tunes-and-home-alone-1.4940775|archive-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film's stunts also created tension for the crew during shooting. Columbus said, \"Every time the stunt guys did one of those stunts it wasn't funny. We'd watch it, and I would just pray that the guys were alive.\"<ref name=\"EW2016\" /> Stunts were originally prepared with safety harnesses, but because of their visibility on camera, the film's final stunts were performed without them.<ref name=\"EW2016\" /> According to ''[[BuzzFeed|Buzzfeed]]'', an injury had occurred between Pesci and Culkin during one of the rehearsals where \"Harry tries to bite off Kevin's finger.\" Culkin still has the scar.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Music===\n{{main|Home Alone: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack}}\nInitially Columbus hoped to have [[Bruce Broughton]] score the films, and early posters listed him as the composer. However, Broughton was busy with ''[[The Rescuers Down Under]]'', and he had to cancel at the last minute.<ref name=EW2016/> Columbus was later able to get in touch with [[Steven Spielberg]], who helped him contact [[John Williams]] to produce the final score.<ref name=EW2016/> Christmas songs, such as \"[[O Holy Night]]\" and \"[[Carol of the Bells]]\", are featured prominently in the film, as well as the film's theme song \"Somewhere in My Memory\". The soundtrack was released by [[Sony Classical]] on cassette on December 4, 1990,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202083813/https://www.amazon.com/Home-Alone-Originl-Soundtrack-Various/dp/B0000027BS/|title=Home Alone-Original Soundtrack|last=|first=|date=|website=Amazon|publisher=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.amazon.com/Home-Alone-Originl-Soundtrack-Various/dp/B0000027BS/|archive-date=2015-02-02|accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref> and on CD on May 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726154742/https://www.amazon.com/Home-Alone-Original-Picture-Soundtrack/dp/B0000027BR|title=Home Alone: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|last=|first=|date=|website=Amazon|publisher=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.amazon.com/Home-Alone-Original-Picture-Soundtrack/dp/B0000027BR/|archive-date=2018-07-26|accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\n''Home Alone'' was first premiered in Chicago on November 10, 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531063056/https://patch.com/illinois/winnetka/home-alone-25-years-later-how-it-all-began|title='Home Alone' 25 Years Later, And How it All Began|last=Moran|first=Tim|date=November 13, 2015|website=|publisher=patch.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://patch.com/illinois/winnetka/home-alone-25-years-later-how-it-all-began|archive-date=May 31, 2019|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> It was given a wide release on November 16, 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405092005/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Home-Alone#tab=summary|title=Home Alone (1990)|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=The Numbers|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Home-Alone#tab=summary|archive-date=2020-04-05|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> ''Home Alone'' was first released by [[20th Century Fox]] on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] on August 23, 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411175534/https://ew.com/article/1991/08/23/home-alone-3/|title=Home Alone|last=Burr|first=Ty|date=August 23, 1991|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://ew.com/article/1991/08/23/home-alone-3/|archive-date=April 11, 2020|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> It was later released on [[DVD]] on October 5, 1999 as a basic package.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130021308/https://www.moviefone.com/movie/home-alone/3777/main/|title=Home Alone (1990)|last=|first=|date=October 5, 1999|website=|publisher=moviefone.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.moviefone.com/movie/home-alone/3777/main/|archive-date=2017-11-30|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The film was released on [[Blu-ray]] on December 2, 2008, titled Family Fun Edition,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200104063120/https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Home-Alone-Blu-ray/1914/|title=Home Alone Blu-ray Family Fun Edition|last=|first=|date=December 2, 2008|website=|publisher=blu-ray.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Home-Alone-Blu-ray/1914/|archive-date=January 4, 2020|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> and was released alongside ''Home Alone 2: Lost in New York'' in a collection pack on October 5, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161212114505/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Home-Alone-Collection-Blu-ray/15620/|title=Home Alone Collection Blu-ray Home Alone / Home Alone 2: Lost in New York|last=|first=|date=October 5, 2010|website=|publisher=blu-ray.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Home-Alone-Collection-Blu-ray/15620/|archive-date=December 12, 2016|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The film was reissued again on DVD and Blu-ray on October 6, 2015, alongside all five ''Home Alone'' franchise films, titled Home Alone: 25th Anniversary Ultimate Collector's Christmas Edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813014236/https://www.tribute.ca/news/home-alone-25th-anniversary-ultimate-collectors-christmas-edition-on-blu-ray-and-dvd/2015/10/06/|title=Home Alone: 25th Anniversary Ultimate Collector\u2019s Christmas Edition on Blu-ray and DVD|last=Fernandes|first=Marriska|date=October 6, 2015|website=|publisher=tribute.ca|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.tribute.ca/news/home-alone-25th-anniversary-ultimate-collectors-christmas-edition-on-blu-ray-and-dvd/2015/10/06/|archive-date=August 13, 2019|access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Home Alone'' grossed $285.8 million in the United States and Canada and $190.9 million in other countries for a worldwide total of $476.7 million, against a production budget of $18 million.<ref name=mojo /> In its opening weekend, ''Home Alone'' grossed $17 million from 1,202 theaters, averaging $14,211 per site and just 6% of the final total and added screens over the next six weeks, with a peak screen count of 2,174 during its eighth weekend at the start of January 1991.<ref name=\"Forbes\" /> ''Home Alone'' proved so popular that it stayed in theaters well past the Christmas season. It was the {{Abbr|No.|Number}} 1 film at the box office for 12 straight weeks, from its release weekend of November 16\u201318, 1990 through the weekend of February 1\u20133, 1991.<ref>{{cite news|last=Broeske|first=Pat H.|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411145540/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-01-14-ca-310-story.html|title=Home Alone in 9th Week as No. 1 Film : Movies: 'Godfather Part III' takes dramatic slide from second to sixth place in its third week out. 'Awakenings' is in second.|date=January 14, 1991|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 1, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-01-14-ca-310-story.html|archive-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614122520/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/16/home-alone-at-25-how-i-forgave-a-mediocre-movie-for-becoming-a-box-office-champion/|title='Home Alone' At 25: How I Forgave A Mediocre Movie For Becoming A Box Office Champion|author=Mendelson|first=Scott|date=November 16, 2015|work=[[Forbes]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/16/home-alone-at-25-how-i-forgave-a-mediocre-movie-for-becoming-a-box-office-champion/|archive-date=2018-06-14|accessdate=November 16, 2015}}</ref> It was dethroned from the top spot when ''[[Sleeping with the Enemy (film)|Sleeping with the Enemy]]'' opened with $13 million.<ref name=\"Forbes\" /> It nevertheless remained a top ten draw at the box office until the weekend of April 26 that year, which was well past Easter weekend. It made two more appearances in the top ten (the weekend of May 31\u2013June 2 and the weekend of June 14\u201316) before finally falling out of the top ten.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405001943/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl3629745665/weekend/|title=Home Alone (1990) - Weekend Box Office Results|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=homealone.htm|archive-date=2020-04-05|accessdate=December 24, 2007}}</ref> After over nine months into its run, the film had earned 16x its debut weekend and ended up making a final gross of $285,761,243, the top-grossing film of its year in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061113051007/http://movies.go.com/boxoffice?cat=1990|title=Movie box office results for the top 50 movies of 1990|last=|first=|date=|website=Movies.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://movies.go.com/boxoffice?cat=1990|archive-date=2006-11-13|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The film is listed in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as the highest-grossing live-action comedy ever<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714122844/https://movie-gazette.com/1081|title=Home Alone - Movie Review|last=Panton|first=Gary|date=2004-12-13|website=Movie Gazette|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://movie-gazette.com/1081|archive-date=2011-07-04|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> and held the record until it was overtaken by ''[[The Hangover Part II]]'' in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003222536/https://www.etonline.com/home-alone-reboot-in-the-works-at-disney-130001|title='Home Alone' Reboot In the Works at Disney|last=Calvario|first=Liz|date=2019-08-06|website=Entertainment Tonight|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.etonline.com/home-alone-reboot-in-the-works-at-disney-130001|archive-date=2019-10-03|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nBy the time it had run its course in theaters, ''Home Alone'' was the [[List of highest-grossing films|third-highest-grossing film of all time worldwide]], as well as in [[List of highest-grossing films in Canada and the United States|the United States and Canada]] behind only ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' ($322 million at the time) and ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' ($399 million at that time), according to the home video box. [[Box Office Mojo]] estimates that the film sold over 67.7 million tickets in the United States.<ref name=mojo /> It was also the highest-grossing Christmas film until it was surpassed by ''[[The Grinch (film)|Dr. Seuss' The Grinch]]'' in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619183940/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/12/22/top-grossing-christmas-films-time/?frame=3136318|title=The top-grossing Christmas films of all time|date=December 25, 2016|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-04-11|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/picture-galleries/11309676/The-top-grossing-Christmas-films-of-all-time.html?frame=3136318|archive-date=2017-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217210226/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt2709692/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|title=Dr. Seuss' The Grinch|last=|first=|date=|website=Box Office Mojo|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt2709692/?ref_=bo_se_r_1|archive-date=2019-12-17|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref> According to [[William Goldman]], the film's success prompted the creation of a Hollywood verb: \"to be ''Home Aloned''\", meaning to have a film's box office reduced by the impact of ''Home Alone''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Goldman |first=William |date=2001 |title=The Big Picture? Who Killed Hollywood and Other Essays |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Zt7TGNB8qyQC&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&q=%22to%20be%20home%20aloned%22 |publisher=Applause Theatre Books |page=49 |isbn=978-1557834607 |accessdate=January 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Home Alone'' holds an approval rating of 65% based on 54 reviews, with an average rating of 5.65/10. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''Home Alone''{{'}}s uneven but frequently funny premise stretched unreasonably thin is buoyed by Macaulay Culkin's cute performance and strong supporting stars.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712222710/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/home_alone/|title=Home Alone Movie Reviews|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/home_alone/|archive-date=2019-06-12|accessdate=August 7, 2017}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating, it has a score of 63 out of 100, based on 9 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205113241/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/home-alone|title=Home Alone Reviews|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/home-alone|archive-date=2019-12-05|accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= December 20, 2018 |access-date= July 24, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' magazine praised the film for its cast.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112143006/http://variety.com/1989/film/reviews/home-alone-1200428389/|title=Variety Reviews - Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117791714?refcatid=31|archive-date=2013-11-12|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]}}</ref> Jeanne Cooper of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' praised the film for its comedic approach.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cooper|first=Jeanne|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406160806/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/homealonepgcooper_a09ecc.htm|title=Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/homealonepgcooper_a09ecc.htm|archive-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Hal Hinson, also of ''The Washington Post'', praised Columbus' direction and Culkin's performance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hinson|first=Hal|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225112000/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/homealonepghinson_a0a9b9.htm|title=Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/homealonepghinson_a0a9b9.htm|archive-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> Although Caryn James of ''[[The New York Times]]'' complained that the film's first half is \"flat and unsurprising as its cute little premise suggests\", she praised the second half for its slapstick humor. She also praised the dialogue between Kevin and Marley, as well as the film's final scenes.<ref>{{cite news|last=James|first=Caryn|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417184530/https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/16/movies/review-film-holiday-black-comedy-for-modern-children.html|title=Movie Review - Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE6D8143DF935A25752C1A966958260|archive-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film a {{frac|2|1|2}} out of a 4-star rating and 2 thumbs down. He compared the elaborate booby-traps in the film to [[Rube Goldberg machine]]s, writing \"they're the kinds of traps that any 8-year-old could devise, if he had a budget of tens of thousands of dollars and the assistance of a crew of movie special effects people\" and criticized the plot as \"so implausible that it makes it hard for [him] to really care about the plight of the kid [Kevin]\". However, he praised Culkin's performance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20180918123627/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/home-alone-1990|title=Home Alone|date=November 16, 1990|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19901116/REVIEWS/11160302|archive-date=2019-08-18|authorlink=Roger Ebert}}</ref>\n\nOwen Gleiberman of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' magazine gave the film a \"D\" grade, criticizing the film for its \"sadistic festival of adult-bashing\". Gleiberman said that \"[John] Hughes is pulling our strings as though he'd never learn to do anything else\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190904145938/https://ew.com/article/2007/07/25/home-alone-2/|title=Home Alone|date=July 25, 2007|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318682,00.html|archive-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> Peter Bradshaw of ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film 3 out of a 5-star rating and praised Culkin's \"vivid screen presence, almost incandescent with confidence.\" However, he criticised his acting, calling it \"a bit broad and mannered\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200407214024/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/nov/30/home-alone-review-yuletide-rerelease|title=Home Alone review \u2013 1990 Christmas cracker resurfaces|date=2018-11-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-21|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/nov/30/home-alone-review-yuletide-rerelease|archive-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Ali Barclay of the ''[[BBC Online|BBC]]'' wrote \"Culkin walks a fine line between annoyance and endearment throughout the film.\" He also called ''Home Alone'' \"a film which manages to capture some of the best qualities of Christmas\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190919113621/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/04/home_alone_1990_review.shtml|title=BBC - Films - review - Home Alone|last=Barclay|first=Ali|date=2000-12-04|website=BBC|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/04/home_alone_1990_review.shtml|archive-date=2019-09-19|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nNaomi Barnwell of ''Roobla'' said that \"''Home Alone'' has all the ingredients that make for a great kids\u2019 film\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://roobla.com/movies/1419/home-alone-1990/|title=Review: Home Alone (1990)|last=Barnwell|first=Naomi|date=2010-12-13|website=Roobla|language=en-GB|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221203921/https://roobla.com/movies/1419/home-alone-1990/|archive-date=2020-02-21|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> Adrian Turner of Radio Times commented \"[Home Alone is] a celebration of enterprise that captured the heart and wickedness of every child on the planet.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228121514/https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cnmkh/home-alone/|title=Home Alone \u2013 review {{!}} cast and crew, movie star rating and where to watch film on TV and online|last=Turner|first=Adrian|date=|website=Radio Times|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cnmkh/home-alone/|archive-date=2016-12-28|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> According to [[TV Guide|''TV Guide'']], \"[''Home Alone'']'s slapstick falls flat and only the pain remains.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221203931/https://www.tvguide.com/movies/home-alone/review/128202/|title=Home Alone {{!}} TV Guide|last=|first=|date=|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/home-alone/review/128202|archive-date=2020-02-21|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> Marielle Sabbag of ''Vocal'' wrote \"Everything about [''Home Alone''] is beautiful and has a realistic quality.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222133119/https://vocal.media/geeks/home-alone-a-movie-review|title='Home Alone'\u2014A Movie Review|last=Sabbag|first=Marielle|date=|website=Geeks|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://vocal.media/geeks/home-alone-a-movie-review|archive-date=2020-02-22|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> Peter Rainer of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' criticised the fact that \"there is a reason why this film plays better as a trailer than as a full-length film.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222133123/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-11-16-ca-4515-story.html|title=MOVIE REVIEW : Kid Plays It for Laughs in 'Home Alone'|last=Rainer|first=Peter|date=1990-11-16|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1990-11-16-ca-4515-story.html|archive-date=2020-02-22|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the film's release, ''Home Alone'' gradually became a Christmas classic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715115846/https://www.joe.ie/movies-tv/10-reasons-why-home-alone-is-a-must-watch-during-the-christmas-season-478902|title=10 reasons why Home Alone will always be a Christmas classic|last=Moore|first=Paul|date=|website=JOE.ie|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.joe.ie/movies-tv/10-reasons-why-home-alone-is-a-must-watch-during-the-christmas-season-478902|archive-date=2018-07-15|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200412165419/https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/is-home-alone-the-best-christmas-movie-of-all-time/|title=Home Alone: the best Christmas movie of all time?|last=Clayton|first=James|date=2019-11-16|website=Den of Geek|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/home-alone/33420/home-alone-the-best-christmas-movie-of-all-time|archive-date=2020-04-12|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193249/https://archive.nerdist.com/home-alone-christmas-classic-breakdown/|title=What Makes HOME ALONE a Christmas Classic? \u2014 Nerdist|last=Walsh|first=Michael|date=2017-12-08|website=Nerdist|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.nerdist.com/home-alone-christmas-classic-breakdown/|archive-date=2020-02-23|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193250/https://www.vox.com/2015/11/16/9731584/home-alone-popular|title=Home Alone's enduring popularity, explained|last=Pai|first=Tanya|date=2015-11-16|website=Vox|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.vox.com/2015/11/16/9731584/home-alone-popular|archive-date=2020-02-23|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> It was praised for its quotable phrases,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223194751/https://parade.com/955037/stefanieparker/home-alone-quotes/|title=Here Are the 31 Most Iconic Quotes From Home Alone\u2014Keep the Change, Ya Filthy Animal|last=Parker|first=Stefanie|date=2019-11-19|website=Parade|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://parade.com/955037/stefanieparker/home-alone-quotes/|archive-date=2020-02-23|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> morals,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193249/https://www.theodysseyonline.com/home-alone-lessons-learned-|title=Lessons Learned From Watching Home Alone|last=|first=|date=2019-01-09|website=The Odyssey Online|language=en-us|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/home-alone-lessons-learned-|archive-date=2020-02-23|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> traps,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bartleet|first=Larry|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193248/https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/kevin-mccallisters-25-cruellest-home-alone-traps-25-years-on-from-the-original-764578|title=Kevin McCallister's 25 cruellest Home Alone traps {{!}} NME|date=2015-12-19|work=NME|access-date=2020-02-23|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/kevin-mccallisters-25-cruellest-home-alone-traps-25-years-on-from-the-original-764578|archive-date=2020-02-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> and main character.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200223193248/https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/12/home-alone-is-basically-torture-porn/420471/|title='Home Alone': Beloved Holiday Torture Porn|last=Garber|first=Megan|date=2015-12-15|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/12/home-alone-is-basically-torture-porn/420471/|archive-date=2020-02-23|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> Hannah-Rose Yee of [[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]] called the ending \"very sweet\" and praised the score from John Williams, calling it \"fantastic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200410100425/https://www.stylist.co.uk/life/home-alone-review-macaulay-culkin-christmas-movie-classic-rewatch/334383|title=Home Alone: 19 thoughts I had watching the Christmas classic for the first time|last=Rose-Yee|first=Hannah|date=|website=Stylist|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.stylist.co.uk/life/home-alone-review-macaulay-culkin-christmas-movie-classic-rewatch/334383|archive-date=2020-04-10|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Christopher Hooton of The Independent also praised the film, calling the film-within-a-film ''Angels with Filthy Souls'' \"a fond footnote in cinema history.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204105120/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/home-alone-cinemas-macaulay-culkin-john-hughes-behind-the-scenes-joe-pesci-john-candy-a8665336.html|title=Why Home Alone is back in cinemas, and why it won't leave our hearts|last=Hooton|first=Christopher|date=2019-12-03|website=The Indepedent|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/home-alone-cinemas-macaulay-culkin-john-hughes-behind-the-scenes-joe-pesci-john-candy-a8665336.html|archive-date=2019-12-04|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Matt Talbot from Simcoe.com said that the Wet Bandits were \"fantastic\" and \"never [got] old\" on \"repeat viewings.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307220106/https://www.simcoe.com/whatson-story/2052295-movie-review-home-alone/|title=MOVIE REVIEW: Home Alone|last=Talbot|first=Matt|date=2012-12-17|website=Simcoe.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.simcoe.com/whatson-story/2052295-movie-review-home-alone/|archive-date=2019-03-07|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Michael Walsh of Nerdist noted the church scene as \"One of the best, most touching scenes [in the film]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223193249/https://archive.nerdist.com/home-alone-christmas-classic-breakdown/|title=What Makes HOME ALONE a Christmas Classic?|last=Walsh|first=Michael|date=2017-12-08|website=Nerdist|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.nerdist.com/home-alone-christmas-classic-breakdown/|archive-date=2020-02-23|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nAt the [[12th Youth in Film Awards]], Macaulay Culkin won Best Young Actor Starring in a Motion Picture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms12.htm|title=Twelfth Annual Youth in Film Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=YoungArtistAwards.org|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707191726/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms12.htm|archive-date=2011-07-07|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref> The film was nominated for two [[Academy Award]]s, one for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]], which was written by [[John Williams]], and the other for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"Somewhere in My Memory\", music by Williams and lyrics by [[Leslie Bricusse]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1354610533731 |title=Home Alone search |work=The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |accessdate=December 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130415161322/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1354610533731 |archivedate=April 15, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Accusations of plagiarism===\nThe 1989 [[Cinema of France|French film]] ''[[3615 code P\u00e8re No\u00ebl]]'', which is about a young boy who is home alone with his elderly grandfather and has to fend off a home invader dressed up as [[Santa Claus]], has been noted for its plot similarities to ''Home Alone''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418032406/https://www.20minutes.fr/culture/1756103-20151224-video-pere-noel-mode-trash|title=Le p\u00e8re No\u00ebl en mode trash|last=Demoulin|first=Anne|date=24 December 2015|website=20minutes.fr|publisher=[[20 minutes (France)|20 minutes]]|language=fr|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.20minutes.fr/culture/1756103-20151224-video-pere-noel-mode-trash|archive-date=2019-04-18|accessdate=24 December 2016}}</ref> ''3615 code P\u00e8re No\u00ebl'' director Ren\u00e9 Manzor threatened the makers of ''Home Alone'' with legal action on the grounds of plagiarism, alleging that ''Home Alone'' was a remake of his film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412171138/https://www.vanityfair.fr/culture/ecrans/articles/ces-choses-que-vous-ignorez-encore-sur-maman-jai-rate-lavion-/48735|title=14 choses que vous ignorez encore sur ''Maman, j'ai rat\u00e9 l'avion''|last=Vanwetswinkel|first=Margaux|date=15 December 2016|website=vanityfair.fr|publisher=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|language=fr|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.vanityfair.fr/culture/cinema/articles/ces-choses-que-vous-ignorez-encore-sur-maman-jai-rate-lavion-/48735|archive-date=2020-04-12|accessdate=24 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124074001/https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/15/movies/film-hollywood-law-whose-idea-is-it-anyway.html?pagewanted=2|title=Hollywood Law: Whose Idea Is It, Anyway?|last=Horowitz|first=Joy|date=15 March 1992|website=nytimes.com|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/15/movies/film-hollywood-law-whose-idea-is-it-anyway.html?pagewanted=2|archive-date=2020-01-24|accessdate=23 December 2016}}</ref> ''3615 code P\u00e8re No\u00ebl'' was not released in the United States during its original theatrical run in January 1990 and did not become widely available there until 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131194718/https://www.americangenrefilm.com/theatrical-film-catalog/dial-code-santa-claus-aka-deadly-games/|title=American Genre Film Archive DIAL CODE SANTA CLAUS|last=|first=|date=|website=www.americangenrefilm.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.americangenrefilm.com/theatrical-film-catalog/dial-code-santa-claus-aka-deadly-games/|archive-date=2020-01-31|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==Franchise==\n{{main|Home Alone (franchise)}}\n===Sequels===\nThe film was followed by a commercially successful sequel in 1992, ''[[Home Alone 2: Lost in New York|Lost in New York]]'', which brought back most of the first film's cast. Culkin was paid $4.5 million to appear in the sequel, compared to $110,000 for the original.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211152658/https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/59269|title=AFI{{!}}Catalog - Home Alone 2: Lost in New York|last=|first=|date=|website=catalog.afi.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/59269|archive-date=2020-02-11|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The film within a film, ''Angels with Filthy Souls'', had a sequel in ''Home Alone 2'', ''Angels with Even Filthier Souls''. Both ''Angels'' meta-films featured character actor [[Ralph Foody]] as stereotypical 1930s mobster Johnny.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205025718/https://thefw.com/things-you-didnt-know-about-home-alone/|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About 'Home Alone'|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=The FW|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://thefw.com/things-you-didnt-know-about-home-alone/|archive-date=2020-02-05|accessdate=April 9, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Home Alone 3]]'' was released in 1997; it has entirely different actors and characters as well as a different storyline, with Hughes writing the screenplay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404100501/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/home-alone-3-1997|title=Home Alone 3 movie review & film summary (1997) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/home-alone-3-1997|archive-date=2020-04-04|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nA fourth [[Made for TV film|made-for-TV film]] followed in 2002, ''[[Home Alone 4|Home Alone 4: Taking Back the House]]''. The movie features some of the same characters who were in the first two films, but with a new cast and a storyline that does not fall into the same continuity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222003218/https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cw9z5/home-alone-4/|title=Home Alone 4 \u2013 review {{!}} cast and crew, movie star rating and where to watch film on TV and online|last=|first=|date=|website=Radio Times|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cw9z5/home-alone-4/|archive-date=2019-12-22|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> On November 25, 2012, a fifth film, ''[[Home Alone: The Holiday Heist|The Holiday Heist]],'' premiered during [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] Family's Countdown to [[25 Days of Christmas]] programming event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/10/05/abc-family-presents-countdown-to-25-days-of-christmas-starting-sunday-november-18/151780/|title=ABC Family Presents 'Countdown to 25 Days of Christmas' Starting Sunday, November 18|last=Bibel|first=Sara|date=October 5, 2012|website=TV by the Numbers|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014134337/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/10/05/abc-family-presents-countdown-to-25-days-of-christmas-starting-sunday-november-18/151780/|archive-date=2012-10-14|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref> Similarly to the third film, it does not focus on the McCallister family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202124527/http://terriblemoviesforterriblepeople.com/2014/12/home-alone-the-holiday-heist-2012.html|title=Home Alone the Holiday Heist \u2013 2012|last=|first=|date=2014-12-08|website=Terrible Movies For Terrible People|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://terriblemoviesforterriblepeople.com/2014/12/home-alone-the-holiday-heist-2012.html|archive-date=2020-02-02|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n===Reboot===\nOn August 6, 2019, [[Disney]] announced plans to reboot the franchise on its [[Disney+]] [[Streaming media|streaming service]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309095853/https://deadline.com/2019/08/disney-plus-home-alone-night-at-the-museum-reboots-fox-1202662998/|title=Disney+ To Revive 'Home Alone'|author=Hayes|first=Dade|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|date=August 6, 2019|website=Deadline|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/disney-plus-home-alone-night-at-the-museum-reboots-fox-1202662998/|archive-date=2020-03-09|accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> On December 10, 2019, [[Archie Yates]], [[Ellie Kemper]], and [[Rob Delaney]] were announced as the cast for a reboot. Yates will not play Kevin, and will have a new story. The story reportedly \"sees Kemper and Delaney play a wife and husband who, in order to save their home from financial ruin, go to war with a kid who has stolen a priceless heirloom.\" [[Dan Mazer]] will direct, from a script by [[Mikey Day]] and [[Streeter Seidell]], and produced by Hutch Parker and Dan Wilson. The film will be a production of [[20th Century Fox]], and marks the first Fox produced project on Disney+. It is set to film in early 2020 in Canada.<ref name=\"archiereboot\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200105154032/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jojo-rabbit-breakout-archie-yates-lead-home-alone-reboot-1261606|title='Jojo Rabbit' Breakout Archie Yates to Lead \u2018Home Alone\u2019 Reboot|last1=Galuppo|first1=Mia|date=|website=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jojo-rabbit-breakout-archie-yates-lead-home-alone-reboot-1261606|archive-date=2020-01-05|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"rebootcast\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409064558/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/home-alone-reboot-archie-yates-ellie-kemper-rob-delaney-1203432212/|title=\u2018Home Alone\u2019 Reboot Taps \u2018Jojo Rabbit\u2019s\u2019 Archie Yates, Ellie Kemper, Rob Delaney (EXCLUSIVE)|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|date=|website=Variety|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/home-alone-reboot-archie-yates-ellie-kemper-rob-delaney-1203432212/|archive-date=2020-04-09|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Homages==\nThe music video for [[Snoop Dogg]]'s 1994 single \"[[Gin and Juice]]\" opens with a gag where, after a teenaged Snoop's parents have left him to watch the house in their absence, he places his hands to his face and yells in the manner of Kevin McCallister in the first film, while a title comes on screen reading \"Home Boy Alone.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202101636/https://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/18468/1/gin-and-juice-turns-20-gettin-loose-for-a-good-reason|title=Gin and Juice turns 20: Gettin' loose for a good reason|last=Dazed|first=|date=2014-01-16|website=Dazed|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/18468/1/gin-and-juice-turns-20-gettin-loose-for-a-good-reason|archive-date=2020-02-02|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Culkin reprised his role as an adult Kevin McCallister in the inaugural episode of the [[Jack Dishel]] web series, \"DRYVRS\", where a visibly disturbed Kevin recounts his experience of being left home alone by his family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531074926/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/see-macaulay-culkin-revisit-traumatized-home-alone-character-55069/|title=See Macaulay Culkin Revisit Traumatized 'Home Alone' Character|author=Ehrlich|first=David|date=December 17, 2015|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/videos/see-macaulay-culkin-revisit-traumatized-home-alone-character-20151217|archive-date=2019-05-31|accessdate=December 18, 2015}}</ref> In response to Culkin's video, Daniel Stern appeared in a short video reprising his role as Marv, released in conjunction with Stern's [[Reddit#IAmA and AMA|Reddit AMA]], where he pleads for Harry to return to help protect him against Kevin's traps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190827164938/https://people.com/celebrity/the-wet-bandits-are-back-daniel-stern-releases-a-video-response-to-macaulay-culkins-home-alone-parody/|title=The Wet Bandits Are Back! Daniel Stern Releases a Video Response to Macaulay Culkin's Home Alone Parody|author=Pearl|first=Diana|date=December 26, 2015|work=People Magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://www.people.com/article/daniel-stern-video-response-macaulay-culkin-home-alone-video|archive-date=2019-08-27|accessdate=December 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 2016 Christmas-set horror film ''[[Better Watch Out]]'' includes a scene where a character who is obsessed with the ''Home Alone'' films demonstrates how, in real life, it would be deadly for someone to be hit in the face with a paint can swung from a distance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200407230205/https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3597558/revisiting-better-watch-memorable-home-alone-inspired-kill/|title=Revisiting \u2018Better Watch Out\u2019 and Its Memorable \u2018Home Alone\u2019 Inspired Kill!|last=Navarro|first=Meagan|date=2019-12-18|website=Bloody Disgusting!|language=en-US|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3597558/revisiting-better-watch-memorable-home-alone-inspired-kill/|archive-date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\nOn December 15, 2018, Culkin made a guest appearance as himself in an episode of ''[[Angry Video Game Nerd|The Angry Video Game Nerd]]'' to review multiple video game adaptations of the first two ''Home Alone'' films, as well as a gameplay session of [[The Pagemaster (video game)|''The Pagemaster'']] with [[James Rolfe]] and [[Mike Matei]] in the days following that episode's release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190804153639/https://www.polygon.com/2018/12/16/18143355/angry-video-game-nerd-macaulay-culkin-home-alone-video-games|title=Macaulay Culkin teams with Angry Video Game Nerd to dump on Home Alone|last1=Good|first1=Owen S.|date=December 16, 2018|website=Polygon|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/12/16/18143355/angry-video-game-nerd-macaulay-culkin-home-alone-video-games|archive-date=2019-08-04|accessdate=December 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 19, 2018, Culkin would once again reprise his role as an adult Kevin McCallister in a 60 second advertisement for [[Google Assistant]], titled ''Home Alone Again.'' The commercial contains [[Shot-for-shot|shot for shot remakes]] of scenes from the film. Google Assistant helps Kevin set up the house to look active by remotely turning on lights, devices, and setting up cutouts of people, in order to have the thieves parked in a van outside (presumably Harry and Marv) steer clear of the house.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Parker|first1=Ryan|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190327091419/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/macaulay-culkin-creates-home-alone-scenes-google-assistant-ad-1170770|title=Macaulay Culkin Re-Creates 'Home Alone' Scenes for Google Assistant Ad|date=December 19, 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 21, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/macaulay-culkin-creates-home-alone-scenes-google-assistant-ad-1170770|archive-date=2019-03-27}}</ref> Additionally, Joe Pesci also reprised his role as Harry, only for his voice making a small cameo. Pesci later appeared in another ad where he watches the short with his friends and jokes about his brief cameo.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Scott|first=Ryan|date=February 1, 2019|title=Joe Pesci returns in new Home Alone Google commercial|url=https://movieweb.com/home-alone-joe-pesci-google-assistant-commercial/|work=[[MovieWeb]]|accessdate=February 3, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202034213/https://movieweb.com/home-alone-joe-pesci-google-assistant-commercial/|archivedate=February 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Novelization==\n''Home Alone'' ({{ISBN|0-590-55066-7}}) was novelized by [[Todd Strasser]] and published by [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]] in 1990 to coincide with the film.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Home_Alone.html?id=D4FSjlUEIGsC&redir_esc=y|title=Home Alone|last=Strasser|first=Todd|date=1990|publisher=Scholastic|isbn=978-0-590-44668-6|language=en}}</ref> On October 6, 2015, to celebrate the 25th anniversary of the movie, an illustrated book by Kim Smith and [[Quirk Books]] was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20171129225735/https://www.buzzfeed.com/krystieyandoli/i-made-my-family-disappear?utm_term=.xejxR8eZx|title=This Illustrated \"Home Alone\" Storybook Will Make You So Excited For Christmas|last=Yandoli|first=Krystie Lee|date=November 9, 2015|website=|publisher=BuzzFeed|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/krystieyandoli/i-made-my-family-disappear|archive-date=2017-11-29|accessdate=April 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Home Alone: The Classic Illustrated Storybook |publisher=Quirk Books |isbn=1594748586}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1990]]\n* [[List of films featuring home invasions]], a plot device in thriller films that ''Home Alone'' lampoons<ref>{{cite news|last=Sragow|first=Michael|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20191223202450/https://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/bs-xpm-2010-12-23-bs-ae-sragow-rail-1224-20101223-story.html|title='Home Alone' is the Charles' post-Christmas gift for kids, parents and hipsters|date=December 23, 2010|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|access-date=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/bs-xpm-2010-12-23-bs-ae-sragow-rail-1224-20101223-story.html|archive-date=2019-12-23|quote=For one sequence, the movie becomes a cat-and-mouse cartoon and a lampoon of home-invasion thrillers.}}</ref>\n* [[List of films featuring fictional films]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote|Home Alone}}\n* {{IMDb title|0099785|Home Alone}}\n* {{tcmdb title|36532|Home Alone}}\n* {{Mojo title|homealone|Home Alone}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|home_alone}}\n* {{Metacritic film|home-alone|Home Alone}}\n* [http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1990/0HMLN.php ''Home Alone''] at The Numbers\n\n{{Portal bar|United States|Film|1990s}}\n{{Home Alone}}\n{{Chris Columbus}}\n{{John Hughes}}\n\n[[Category:Home Alone (franchise)]]\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:1990s Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:American children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:American crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Burglary in film]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Chris Columbus]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films produced by John Hughes (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Williams]]\n[[Category:Films set in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by John Hughes (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:Home invasions in film]]\n", "name_user": "Morriswa", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_Alone"}
{"title_page": "JAD (software)", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = JAD\n| logo                   =\n| screenshot             =\n| caption                =\n| developer              = Pavel Kouznetsov\n| released               = Before {{start date and age|1999}}\n| latest release version = 1.5.8g\n| latest release date    = {{start date and age|2006}}\n| programming language   = [[C++]]\n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| language               = English\n| genre                  = [[Software engineering]]\n| license                = Free for non-commercial use (Copyright: Pavel Kouznetsov)\n| website                = {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080214075546/http://www.kpdus.com/jad.html |date=14 February 2008 |title=Original Jad site, including downloads}}}}\n\n'''Jad''' (Java Decompiler) is, {{as of|2011|August|lc=yes}}, an unmaintained [[decompiler]] for the [[Java (programming language)|Java]] programming language.<ref>{{cite conference|last1=Hamilton|first1=James|last2=Danicic|first2=Sebastian|title=An Evaluation of Current Java Bytecode Decompilers|year=2009|pages=129\u2013136|doi=10.1109/SCAM.2009.24|conference=Source Code Analysis and Manipulation, 2009. SCAM '09. Ninth IEEE International Working Conference on|url=https://www.doc.gold.ac.uk/~mas01sd/decompilers.pdf}}</ref>\nJad provides a [[command-line interface|command-line user interface]] to extract [[source code]] from [[class file]]s.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Java Decompiler]]\n*[[Mocha (decompiler)|Mocha]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite conference|last1=Naeem|first1=N.A.|last2=Batchelder|first2=M.|last3=Hendren|first3=L.|title=Metrics for Measuring the Effectiveness of Decompilers and Obfuscators|year=2007|pages=253\u2013258|doi=10.1109/ICPC.2007.27|conference=Program Comprehension, 2007. ICPC '07. 15th IEEE International Conference on|url=http://www.sable.mcgill.ca/publications/techreports/sable-tr-2006-4.pdf}}\n*{{cite conference|first1=Jong-Yih|last1=Kuo|first2=Louisa|last2=Chu|title=Intelligent code analyzer for online course management system|conference=Software Engineering Research, Management and Applications, 2005. Third ACIS International Conference on|year=2005|pages=228\u2013234|doi=10.1109/SERA.2005.47}}\n*{{cite conference|last1=Miecznikowski|first1=J.|last2=Hendren|first2=L.|title=Decompiling Java using staged encapsulation|year=2001|pages=368\u2013374|doi=10.1109/WCRE.2001.957845|conference=Reverse Engineering, 2001. Proceedings. Eighth Working Conference on}}\n*{{cite conference|last1=Tam|first1=V.|last2=Gupta|first2=R.K.|title=Using class decompilers to facilitate the security of Java applications!|volume=1|year=2000|pages=153\u2013158|doi=10.1109/WISE.2000.882387|conference=Web Information Systems Engineering, 2000. Proceedings of the First International Conference on}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080214075546/http://www.kpdus.com/jad.html |date=14 February 2008 |title=Original Jad site, including downloads}}\n* [http://www.softpedia.com/get/Programming/Debuggers-Decompilers-Dissasemblers/JAD.shtml JAD Softpedia Mirror]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jad (Java Decompiler)}}\n[[Category:Java decompilers]]\n[[Category:Disassemblers]]<!-- according to http://classic-web.archive.org/web/20080214075546/http://www.kpdus.com/jad.html -->\n\n\n{{Programming-software-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = JAD\n| logo                   =\n| screenshot             =\n| caption                =\n| developer              = Pavel Kouznetsov\n| released               = Before {{start date and age|1999}}\n| latest release version = 1.5.8g\n| latest release date    = {{start date and age|2006}}\n| programming language   = [[C++]]\n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| language               = English\n| genre                  = [[Software engineering]]\n| license                = Free for non-commercial use (Copyright: Pavel Kouznetsov)\n| website                = {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080214075546/http://www.kpdus.com/jad.html |date=14 February 2008 |title=Original Jad site, including downloads}}}}\n\n'''Jad''' (Java Decompiler) is, {{as of|2011|August|lc=yes}}, an unmaintained [[decompiler]] for the [[Java (programming language)|Java]] programming language.<ref>{{cite conference|last1=Hamilton|first1=James|last2=Danicic|first2=Sebastian|title=An Evaluation of Current Java Bytecode Decompilers|year=2009|pages=129\u2013136|doi=10.1109/SCAM.2009.24|conference=Source Code Analysis and Manipulation, 2009. SCAM '09. Ninth IEEE International Working Conference on|url=https://www.doc.gold.ac.uk/~mas01sd/decompilers.pdf}}</ref>\nJad provides a [[command-line interface|command-line user interface]] to extract [[source code]] from [[class file]]s.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Java Decompiler]]\n*[[Mocha (decompiler)|Mocha]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite conference|last1=Naeem|first1=N.A.|last2=Batchelder|first2=M.|last3=Hendren|first3=L.|title=Metrics for Measuring the Effectiveness of Decompilers and Obfuscators|year=2007|pages=253\u2013258|doi=10.1109/ICPC.2007.27|conference=Program Comprehension, 2007. ICPC '07. 15th IEEE International Conference on|url=http://www.sable.mcgill.ca/publications/techreports/sable-tr-2006-4.pdf}}\n*{{cite conference|first1=Jong-Yih|last1=Kuo|first2=Louisa|last2=Chu|title=Intelligent code analyzer for online course management system|conference=Software Engineering Research, Management and Applications, 2005. Third ACIS International Conference on|year=2005|pages=228\u2013234|doi=10.1109/SERA.2005.47}}\n*{{cite conference|last1=Miecznikowski|first1=J.|last2=Hendren|first2=L.|title=Decompiling Java using staged encapsulation|year=2001|pages=368\u2013374|doi=10.1109/W