]]\n|[[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani \u2013 Goa Campus]], [[Goa]]\n|1st Runner Up\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Rocktaves of Oasis\n|[[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani]], [[Rajasthan]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Wildfire of [[Spring Fest]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Blizzard of Rock of Chaos\n|[[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]], [[Gujarat]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Thunder of Radio Dhoom\n|[[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Strawberry Fields (Indian festival)\n|[[National Law School of India University]], [[Karnataka]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Resonance of [[Festember]]\n|[[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Thunder of Radio Dhoom\n|[[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]]\n|{{won}}\n|Best Vocalist and Best Drummer\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|B-School of Rock of [[Unmaad]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Management Bangalore]], Karnataka\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Wildfire of [[Spring Fest]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|[[Wacken Open Air | Wacken Metal Battle of W:O:A]], hosted by [[Bangalore Open Air]]\n|[[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists of Eastern India''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|[[Synchronicity (Rock Festival, IIT Kanpur) | Synchronicity]] of [[Antaragni]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n|1st Runner Up\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Till Deaf Do We Part of [[Pearl (cultural festival)]]\n|[[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani \u2013 Hyderabad Campus]], [[Telangana]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Decibelz of Xpressions\n|[[Xavier Institute of Management, Bhubaneswar]], [[Odisha]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Hornbill International Rock Contest\n|[[Hornbill Festival]], [[Dimapur]], [[Nagaland]]\n|\n|''Finalists'' along with Best Drummer\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Livewire of [[Mood Indigo (festival)]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Bombay]], [[Maharashtra]]\n|2nd Runner Up\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Rock-O-Phonix of [[Alcheringa (festival)]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Guwahati]], [[Assam]]\n|\n|''Finalists'' along with Best Stage Presence and Drummer\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Decibels of [[Saarang]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Madras]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Thundermarch of Incandescene\n|[[National Institute of Technology, Silchar]], [[Assam]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Hornbill International Rock Contest\n|[[Hornbill Festival]], [[Dimapur]], [[Nagaland]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2020\n|[[Wacken Open Air | Wacken Metal Battle of W:O:A]], hosted by [[Bangalore Open Air]]\n|TopCat CCU, [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists of Eastern India''\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Metallica}}\n[[Category:Indian rock music]]\n[[Category:Indian rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Indian heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Jharkhand]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Indian musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical quintets]]\n[[Category:Articles which contain graphical timelines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian metal band}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Highway 69\n| image           = Highway 69 - Group Photo.jpg\n| caption         = Members of Highway 69. From left to right: [[Alvin Rozario]], John Raj Swami, Binit Barla and Tarang Kerketta.\n| alt             = Group photo of the members in Highway 69 (band).\n| landscape       = yes\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]], [[India]].\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]}}\n| years_active    = 2012\u2013present\n| associated_acts = [[Alvin Rozario]]\n| current_members =\n* Tarang Kerketta (''Dagu'')\n* [[Alvin Rozario]]\n* Binit Barla\n* John Raj Swami\n| past_members    =\n* Nikhil Dhanraj\n* Anugraha Sonal Johnson Mundu\n* Dheeraj Edward\n}}\n\n'''Highway 69''' is an Indian [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band. The band was formed in 2012 in [[Ranchi]] by vocalist Tarang Kerketta and guitarist [[Alvin Rozario]], and has been based in [[Ranchi]] ever-since it's formation. The band has been the winners of numerous battle of band titles across their country and is known for their fast tempos, instrumental and aggressive style of playing. The band has performed twice as the finalists at Hornbill International Rock Contest of [[Hornbill Festival]] in [[Nagaland]] for the year 2017<ref>{{cite web|title=Musical route to national stage|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/jharkhand/musical-route-to-national-stage/cid/1342721|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> and 2018<ref>{{cite web|title=Nine bands to vie for Hornbill Rock Contest finale today|url=https://www.easternmirrornagaland.com/nine-bands-to-vie-for-hornbill-rock-contest-finale-today/|website=Eastern Mirror Nagaland|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref>. Their drummer has also bagged the title of the 'Best Drummer' in the year 2017 at this festival and was felicitated by [[Uday Benegal]] from the [[Indus Creed]] which is a band considered to be the pioneers of the Indian rock music.\n\nHailing from a small place quite unknown to the rest of the country, the band had to face discrimination and hardships in their path to fame. Their artistry and love for music guided them through tough times, on course to become an upcoming popular metal band from [[East India | Eastern India]]. Highway 69 performs extensively all over the country and is evolving with a huge fan base. Currently, the band is working on its debut album.\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and early years (2012\u20132013)===\n[[File:Highway 69 at BIT Mesra Deoghar campus during Utthaan 2012.jpg|thumb|Highway 69 after doing their first show together as a band at Utthaan fest of BIT Mesra (Deoghar campus) in October 2012.\n(From left: Binit Barla, Tarang Kerketta, [[Alvin Rozario]] and Dheeraj Edward.)]]\nHighway 69 was formed in [[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]] in mid-2012 with the founding members being Tarang Kerketta and [[Alvin Rozario]]. Back then, Tarang used to live in [[Jamshedpur]] which is a city approximately 120 km from Ranchi. He was the vocalist of a metal-band based in Jamshedpur called Atript while Alvin was the guitarist for a metal-band in Ranchi called Destiny. Both of them met for the first time during a local battle of the band competition in Ranchi. It is considered that it was the initial place where both of them decided on forming a band of their own.\n\nThe band Highway 69 was started with Tarang on the vocals and Alvin on the guitars, along with that two local musicians named Binit Barla and Dheeraj Edward. Binit used to play bass for Alvin's show while Alvin and Dheeraj were bandmates in their metal band named Destiny. When Alvin and Tarang were forming a band and we're looking for band members, this is when Alvin suggested the names Binit and Dheeraj with whom he had already been performing. Hence the line-up was formed and the band started to practice together and composed their first song called 'Disturbed' and covered other popular metal songs. They went on to participate in a battle of bands competition organized at [[Birla Institute of Technology (Deoghar)]] by Utthaan where the band won the competition along with that Alvin was awarded the best guitarist in the competition. As it was the year-end of 2012, then went on to do few local gigs in Ranchi and Jamshedpur. They also had a major achievement in their early years by winning the Wheels competition organized by TATA Steel in Jamshedpur.\n\n===''Dheeraj quits, Johnson joins the band'' and [[Thunderstrock Festival]] (2013-2014)===\nDheeraj and Alvin both use to be bandmates in their previous metal band. Both had high expectation from their band but weren't able to find that same spirit in that band so they left to form Highway 69. But even before completing one year as the drummer for Highway 69, Dheeraj decided to quit the band citing difficulty in managing his time between the band and his higher studies.\n\n[[File:Highway 69 at IIM Bangalore during Unmaad 2014.jpg|thumb|left|Highway 69 performing at Rockolesseum of Unmaad, the cultural festival of IIM Bangalore]]\nDheeraj was replaced by Anugraha Sonal Johnson Mundu, a local musician who belonged to Alvin's neighbourhood. He joined the band and the band continued with him. With the new line-up, the band won the battle of bands competitions at [[St. Xavier's School, Ranchi]], [[National Institute of Foundry and Forge Technology]] Ranchi, made their appearance in the Avalanche of [[Srijan]] at [[Indian School of Mines, Dhanbad]] and in Rockolesseum of Unmaad, the cultural festival of [[IIM Bangalore]]. Performing in Bangalore became their very first metropolitan show as a band which also required travelling of approximately 1,900 km from their hometown. The Bangalore show became the place where the band got the exposure of various other bands and musicians who were the part of that fest like [[Blackstratblues]], [[Karsh Kale]], [[Farhan Akhtar]] and many others. The band also performed at Detox, which was an initiative by the Government of Jharkhand to promote the local rock & metal music culture. They shared the stage with [[Demonic Resurrection]], [[Girish and The Chronicles]] and other local bands from the city.\n\nLater during mid-2014, Tarang Kerketta took the initiative of starting an inactive rock & metal music festival from their city called [[Thunderstrock Festival]]. It was a charitable music festival started in 2008 with the initiative of promoting the local music scene as well as to donate the funds generated from it to the people in need. Tarang is generally credited in bringing this stagnant music festival back to life again in 2014 with giving the stage to the local bands like Death Note (now Reciprocal), Destiny (band in which Alvin and Dheeraj used to play earlier), Error 404, Virus (John, the drummer of this band later joins Highway 69), Genesis, Highway 69 and Head Motif all the way from [[Darjeeling]], [[West Bengal]].\n\n===Replacement of drummers and winning competitions across India (2015-2018)===\n[[File:Tarang Kerketta, Pepsi MTV Indies - Ranchi Rocks, in 2015.jpg|thumb|Tarang Kerketta performing at Pepsi MTV Indies - Ranchi Rocks: Chapter 1, in 2015]]\nAfter a year since Dheeraj left the band, he again approached the band for joining it. He was considered in the band's line-up once again and eventually, Johnson had to leave who earlier came as the replacement in Dheeraj's place. With Dheeraj once again in the line-up, the band went for participating at i-Rock of Jinks-Pranav at [[National Institute of Foundry and Forge Technology]], Ranchi, Thundermarch at [[National Institute of Technology, Silchar]] and Avalanche of [[Srijan]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology (Indian School of Mines), Dhanbad]]. The band won the competitions at [[NIFFT]] Ranchi and IIT (ISM) Dhanbad but couldn't secure any position at [[NIT Silchar]] (Later in 2016, the band was again shortlisted for the finals at NIT Silchar but they couldn't go to perform and in 2018, they were selected for the third time and this time they even won the competition). The band also headlined the Pepsi MTV Indies - Ranchi Rocks: Chapter 1 in 2015 which had the local bands of Ranchi along with that the headliner band from Bangalore named Live Banned.\n\n[[File:John receiving the Best Drummer award at Hornbill Festival in 2017..jpg|thumb|left|John receiving the Best Drummer award from Uday Benegal of Indus Creed (band) at Hornbill International Rock Contest in 2017.]]\nLater in the year 2015, Dheeraj again decided to leave the band as he wasn't able to continue with regular practice and cope up with Highway 69's regular participating in events which required a lot of travelling throughout the country. So they finally decided on having a permanent drummer who will be committed towards the band. During this time, the band practised with various drummers from [[Ranchi]], [[Jamshedpur]] and even [[Kolkata]] but ultimately settled for John Raj Swami, who was a drummer for a local metal band called Virus who was in the line-up of [[Thunderstrock Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Bipolar Shadows all set to perform at Thunderstrock Festival in Ranchi|url=https://etchronicle.com/bipolar-shadows-all-set-to-perform-at-thunderstrock-festival-in-ranchi/|website=ET Chronicle|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> 2014, which is a festival initiated by Highway 69's vocalist. The band was already familiar with the playing style of John as they have shared the stage in various competitions and music festivals across India. The band went for practice with him and did a couple of few shows in Ranchi and were quite impressed with his playing style and even John agreed in joining the band as their permanent replacement for a drummer. The growing confusion over who'll continue the band as a drummer was finally sorted out. This gave the band it's ample time to practice and compose new songs. John came as a perfect replacement but tensions grew in mid-2017 when due to personal misunderstandings within the band, he was asked to leave the band. But later in the same year itself, he again joined the band and has been with the band ever since. John is quite popular amongst the audience and other fellow musicians because of his aggressive style of drumming along with going shirtless when performing on-stage.\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | footer    = John and Alvin during their performance at Culfest of NIT Jamshedpur in 2016. (top) and Highway 69 after completing their performance at Spring Fest of IIT Kharagpur in 2017. (bottom)\n | image1    = John and Alvin during their performance at NIT Jamshedpur in 2016.jpg\n | width1    = 210\n | image2    = Highway 69 at IIT Kharagpur during Spring Fest 2017.jpg\n | width2    = 210\n}}\n\nWith the new drummer in hand who is regular in practice, the band could finally look forward to participating at some of the biggest and most popular battles of the bands' competition in India. During the span of 2015\u20132018, the band went to participate in festivals across India of which they won the competitions like Fuego - KIIT Fest of [[Kalinga Institute of Industrial Technology]], [[Bhubaneswar]], Blizzard of Rock - Chaos of [[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]], Distortion - Culfest of [[National Institute of Technology, Jamshedpur]], Rocktaves - Oasis of [[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani]],<ref>{{cite web|title=BITS PILANI OASIS ROCK EVENT: ROCKTAVES|url=https://atkt.in/articles/bits-pilani-oasis-rock-event-rocktaves/|website=ATKT.in|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Searock of [[Waves (festival) ]] at [[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani \u2013 Goa Campus]], Till Deaf Do We Part of [[Pearl (cultural festival)]] at [[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani \u2013 Hyderabad Campus]], Resonance of [[Festember]] at [[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]],<ref>{{cite web|title=METAL BAND HIGHWAY 69 WREAK HAVOC AT FESTEMBER|url=https://atkt.in/articles/highway-69-trichy/|website=ATKT.in|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Synchronicity of [[Antaragni]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur]], Decibelz of Xpressions at [[Xavier Institute of Management, Bhubaneswar]] and Thundermarch of Incandescene at [[National Institute of Technology, Silchar]]. The band won the runner-up positions at Wildfire of [[Spring Fest]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]], Strawberry Fields at [[National Law School of India University]], [[Bangalore]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Resigned from the job because Boss did not grant holiday|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/latest-ranchi-news-040533-2381266.html|website=Dainik Bhaskar|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref>, Livewire of [[Mood Indigo (festival)]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Bombay]]<ref>{{cite web|title=IIT Bombay's annual cultural festival Mood Indigo kicks off its Livewire nite|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BdAawjfHexr/?utm_source=ig_web_button_share_sheet|website=Instagram handle of Rolling Stones (India)|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref>, Decibels of [[Saarang]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras]], Rock-o-Phonix of [[Alcheringa (festival)]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Guwahati]] and have been twice declared the finalists at Hornbill International Rock Contest of [[Hornbill Festival]] at Nagaland in 2017<ref>{{cite web|title=Hornbill International Rock Contest: Nine bands to battle it out in grand finale on Friday|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/north-east-india/nagaland/hornbill-international-rock-contest-nine-bands-to-battle-it-out-in-grand-finale-on-friday-4972972/|website=Indian Express|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dimapur to host Hornbill International Rock Contest 2017|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/north-east-india/nagaland/dimapur-to-host-hornbill-international-rock-contest-2017/|website=Indian Express|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bands making it to the finale included...Highway 69 (Ranchi, Jharkhand)|url=http://www.nagalandpost.com/perfect-strangers-wins-hirc-2018/186716.html|website=Nagaland Post|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> John has been awarded as the best drummer at Hornbill Festival in 2017. During their span of covering all the major music competitions across India, the band started to attain national recognization in the music scene and a good amount of fan following as well as positive reception and appreciation from fellow musicians and promoters at the events.\n\nIn the mid-2017, there was some misunderstanding within the band due to which John was removed from the band and in his replacement, a drummer from [[Jamshedpur]] called Nikhil Dhanraj played the drums for Highway 69. With Nikhil, the band did a couple of shows with participation in the competition held at [[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]], [[Tamil Nadu]] and a music master class by Highway 69 at [[Chakradharpur]], [[Jharkhand]]. Within a short span of John's absence, he was again included in the line-up. Also in the same year, the band was shortlisted for the first time in the Eastern-leg of Wacken Metal Battle organized by [[Bangalore Open Air]] alongside Astitiva (now Existence), Reciprocal from Ranchi and [[Chronic Xorn]] from Kolkata but due to the unavailability of their bassist; they did not go for the competition.\n\nAlong with the competitions, the timeline of 2015-2018 was also spent in composing new original songs by the band. The band went unto compose their originals like Beyond Imagination, Don't be the Prisoners, Hope and Origin. Apart from taking part in competitions, they headlined in music festivals of [[Jamshedpur]], [[Ranchi]] and [[Kolkata]] which eventually helped them gain the pace of a popular upcoming metal band in their own state. Having spent a long-time in competitions, the year 2018 was marked as the last year to participate in competitions.\n\n=== Headlining & judging shows, upcoming debut album (2019\u2013present)===\n[[File:Highway 69 after completing their show at Jalpaiguri in 2019..jpg|thumb|left|A group photo with the audience after completing the show at Jalpaiguri in 2019.]]\nDuring the mid-2018, when Tarang started the work for that year's [[Thunderstrock Festival]], he took on-board Tarun Paul Kachhap to manage the promotions of the festival and eventually he made Tarun as the manager for Highway 69. Also by the end of 2018 when the band was returning from Hornbill Festival<ref>{{cite web|title=Ranchi bands Highway 69 and Vikrit in the finals|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/jharkhand/ranchi/news/ranchi-rock-band-highway-69-and-distorted-to-the-final-of-contest-035603-3389144.html|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref> in Nagaland they decided to give an end to participating in music competitions and work in their debut album and give preference to booked shows. With having a long-list of competitions that the band has won, they have been booked as the judges for the competitions in which they themselves once used to be the participants. The band was booked to judge Fuego of KIIT Fest 2019 in [[Kalinga Institute of Industrial Technology]], [[Bhubaneswar]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Highway 69 as the judges for Fuego.|url=https://www.facebook.com/kiitfest/photos/a.754450924636786/2076640085751190/|website=Facebook page of KIIT Fest|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Avalanche of [[Srijan]] 2019 in [[Indian Institute of Technology (Indian School of Mines), Dhanbad]] and twice at Rhapsody of Bitotsav 2019 and 2020 in [[Birla Institute of Technology, Mesra]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The local metal band of Ranchi, Highway 69 performed in the Fusion Arena|url=https://bitmesra.ac.in/naps/11813-2/|website=NAPS of BIT Mesra|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> They even got headliner shows in [[Jorhat]], twice in [[Jalpaiguri]], opening for [[Jubin Nautiyal]], a Bollywood singer at [[Srijan]] of [[Indian Institute of Technology (Indian School of Mines), Dhanbad]], Bitotsav of [[Birla Institute of Technology, Mesra]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Plethora of events enthuse participants at BITOTSAV 2020|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2020/state-editions/plethora-of-events-enthuse-participants-at-bitotsav-2020.html|website=The Pioneer|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> and shows in Ranchi.<ref>{{cite web|title=State to celebrate its 19th year of foundation on November 15|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/state-to-celebrate-its-19th-year-of-foundation-on-november-15.html|website=The Pioneer|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Despite their decision of 2018, which meant to not take part in any competitions, the band went to register for Wacken Metal Battle which is organized by [[Bangalore Open Air]]. It is India's only dedicated Heavy metal open-air music festival which takes place yearly in [[Bangalore]] in collaboration with [[Wacken Open Air]]. The winning band gets an opportunity to play at Wacken Open Air in Germany which is one of the largest heavy metal festivals in the world. The band had earlier registered for the competition in 2017 but couldn't go to perform due to their bassist's unavailability. So they once again gave a try by participating in the competition in 2020 and were shortlisted for the Eastern India-leg of Wacken Metal Battle alongside other [[West Bengal]]-based bands. Highway 69 could not win the competition but the band shared the stage with some really great bands in the competition and witnessed the performance of headliners like [[Chronic Xorn]] and [[Kryptos]].\n\nThe band went for recording their debut album in 2018-2019 but were not impressed with the final recording, mixing and mastering done by the studio. This caused a huge loss for the band also in their album release dates. Currently, all the band members live in different places with Alvin in [[Ranchi]], Binit in [[Khelari]] and John in [[Khunti]] of [[Jharkhand]] state while Tarang lives in [[Angul]] of [[Odisha]] state of India. Despite living in different places, the band generally meets in weekdays for their band practice which requires all the members to take out time and travel to Ranchi (except Alvin who lives in Ranchi). Also with the loss suffered in their album recording, the band has cancelled the plan of recording its album and is currently recording three singles at music studios of [[Kolkata]]. Due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]], their recording dates have been postponed but the band has targeted to release these three singles along with its music videos in the year 2020 itself.\n\n==Band members==\n<!--Do not change the order of the members, as they are in order of instrument to reflect the timeline.-->\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Current members'''\n* Tarang Kerketta \u2013 vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Alvin Rozario]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n* Binit Barla \u2013 bass, backing vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n* John Raj Swami \u2013 drums <small>(2015\u2013present)</small>\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Former members'''\n* Dheeraj Edward \u2013 drums <small>(2012\u20132013 & 2015)</small>\n* Anugraha Sonal Johnson Mundu \u2013 drums <small>(2014)</small>\n* Nikhil Dhanraj \u2013 drums <small>(2017)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:25\nPlotArea = left:90 bottom:80 top:10 right:10\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:10/01/2012 till:{{#time: m/d/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:3\nScaleMajor = increment:1 start:2013\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2013\n\nColors =\n id:vocals value:red    legend:Vocals\n id:guitar value:green  legend:Guitar,_backing_vocals\n id:bass   value:blue   legend:Bass,_backing_vocals\n id:drums  value:orange legend:Drums\n\nLineData =\n at:01/01/2013\n at:01/01/2014\n at:01/01/2015\n at:01/01/2016\n at:01/01/2017\n at:01/01/