la Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani]], [[Rajasthan]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Wildfire of [[Spring Fest]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Blizzard of Rock of Chaos\n|[[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]], [[Gujarat]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Thunder of Radio Dhoom\n|[[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Strawberry Fields (Indian festival)\n|[[National Law School of India University]], [[Karnataka]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Resonance of [[Festember]]\n|[[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Thunder of Radio Dhoom\n|[[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]]\n|{{won}}\n|Best Vocalist and Best Drummer\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|B-School of Rock of [[Unmaad]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Management Bangalore]], Karnataka\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Wildfire of [[Spring Fest]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|[[Wacken Open Air | Wacken Metal Battle of W:O:A]], hosted by [[Bangalore Open Air]]\n|[[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists of Eastern India''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|[[Synchronicity (Rock Festival, IIT Kanpur) | Synchronicity]] of [[Antaragni]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n|1st Runner Up\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Till Deaf Do We Part of [[Pearl (cultural festival)]]\n|[[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani \u2013 Hyderabad Campus]], [[Telangana]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Decibelz of Xpressions\n|[[Xavier Institute of Management, Bhubaneswar]], [[Odisha]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Hornbill International Rock Contest\n|[[Hornbill Festival]], [[Dimapur]], [[Nagaland]]\n|\n|''Finalists'' along with Best Drummer\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Livewire of [[Mood Indigo (festival)]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Bombay]], [[Maharashtra]]\n|2nd Runner Up\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Rock-O-Phonix of [[Alcheringa (festival)]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Guwahati]], [[Assam]]\n|\n|''Finalists'' along with Best Stage Presence and Drummer\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Decibels of [[Saarang]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Madras]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Thundermarch of Incandescene\n|[[National Institute of Technology, Silchar]], [[Assam]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Hornbill International Rock Contest\n|[[Hornbill Festival]], [[Dimapur]], [[Nagaland]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2020\n|[[Wacken Open Air | Wacken Metal Battle of W:O:A]], hosted by [[Bangalore Open Air]]\n|TopCat CCU, [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists of Eastern India''\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Metallica}}\n[[Category:Indian rock music]]\n[[Category:Indian rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Indian heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Jharkhand]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Indian musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical quintets]]\n[[Category:Articles which contain graphical timelines]]\n", "name_user": "Tarun Paul Kachhap", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Highway_69_(band)"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Norman Jackson", "text_new": "{{Other people|Thomas Jackson}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Thomas Norman Jackson\n|honorific_suffix=VC\n|birth_date={{birth date|df=y|1897|2|11}}\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=y|1918|9|27|1897|2|11}}{{KIA}}\n|birth_place= [[Swinton, South Yorkshire]]\n|death_place= [[Canal du Nord]], France\n|placeofburial=Sanders Keep Military Cemetery, [[Graincourt-les-Havrincourt]]\n|image= Thomas Norman Jackson VC.jpg\n|image_size= \n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears=1915&ndash;1918 \n|rank=[[Lance corporal|Lance Corporal]]\n|branch={{army|United Kingdom}}\n|commands= \n|unit=[[Coldstream Guards]]\n|battles= [[World War I]]\n*[[Battle of Cambrai (1917)|Battle of Cambrai]]\n*[[Hundred Days Offensive]]\n**[[Battle of the Canal du Nord]] {{KIA}}\n|awards= [[File:Victoria Cross (UK) ribbon.png|30px]] [[Victoria Cross]]\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Thomas Norman Jackson''' [[Victoria Cross|VC]] (11 February 1897 &ndash; 27 September 1918) was an [[England|English]] soldier of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War I)|British Expeditionary Force]], and posthumous recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]], the highest military award for gallantry in the face of the enemy given to [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces, during the First World War.\n\n==Early life==\nThomas Norman Jackson was born on 11 February 1897 in [[Swinton, South Yorkshire|Swinton]] in [[South Yorkshire]] to Thomas Edwin, a worker at a supplier of mineral water, and Emma Jackson. After completing his schooling, he started working alongside his father. He later took up employment at the Great Central Locomotive Depot, based at Mexborough.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}}\n\n==First World War==\nIn November 1915, Jackson enlisted in the [[British Army]] and, in October 1917, was posted to the 1st Battalion of the [[Coldstream Guards]], which was serving in France on the [[Western Front (WWI)|Western Front]] at the time. He participated in the [[Battle of Cambrai (1917)|Battle of Cambrai]] the following month. He was later promoted to [[lance corporal]].{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}}\n\nOn 27 September 1918, during the [[Hundred Days Offensive]], the Coldstream Guards was engaged in the [[Battle of Canal du Nord]], near Graincourt. Jackson's battalion was tasked with the capture of a canal crossing. Once over the canal, it was to set up defensive positions and make contact with the adjacent 3rd Guards Battalion. On reaching the canal, the advance of Jackson's company, under the command of Captain [[Cyril Frisby]], was halted by barbed wire together with heavy fire from a German machine-gun post under the bridge on the far side of the canal. Jackson, together with Frisby and two others, got through the wire and climbed down into the canal under intense fire. With a further twelve men joining them, the post was captured.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=11\u201312}}\n\nLater in the morning, Jackson was ordered to move forward with a platoon to seize a German-held trench. He was first into the trench, and after killing two German soldiers, he in turn was killed.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}} His grave is at Sanders Keep Military Cemetery, [[Graincourt-les-Havrincourt]], which is to the west of Cambrai.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jackson, Thomas Norman |url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/338360  |website=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n \nFor his actions on 27 September 1918, Jackson was awarded the Victoria Cross (VC),{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|p=31}} one of seven that would be awarded for actions performed on 27 September.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=11\u201312}} The citation for his VC read:\n{{quote|For most conspicuous bravery and self-sacrifice in the attack across the Canal Du Nord, near Graincourt. On the morning of the 27th September, 1918, L./Cpl. Jackson was the first to volunteer to follow Capt. C. H. Frisby, Coldstream Guards, across the Canal du Nord in his rush against an enemy machine-gun post. With two comrades he followed his officer across the Canal, rushed the post, captured the two machine-guns, and so enabled the companies to advance. Later in the morning, L./Cpl. Jackson was the first to jump into a German trench which his platoon had to clear, and after doing further excellent work he was unfortunately killed. Throughout the whole day until he was killed this young N.C.O. showed the greatest valour and devotion to duty and set an inspiring example to all.|[[London Gazette]], 27 November 1918<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31034|date=26 November 1918|page=14040|supp=y }}</ref>}}\n\n[[King George V]] presented Jackson's VC to his parents in a ceremony at Buckingham Palace on 29 March 1919. Also present was Jackson's fianc\u00e9e Daisy Flatt.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|p=13}} Frisby, in attendance at the same ceremony to receive his own award of the VC for his role in the action of 27 September 1918, was able to explain to Jackson's family the circumstances of their relative's VC award. A few months later Frisby travelled to Swindon to unveil a painting commemorating Jackson.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}}\n\n==Medals==\nIn June 1969, Jackson's brother donated his medals, which in addition to the VC also included the [[British War Medal]] and Victory Medal to The Coldstream Guards Regimental Headquarters at [[Wellington Barracks, London|Wellington Barracks]] in London, where they are on display.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Gliddon|first=Gerald|title=The Final Days 1918|series=[[VCs of the First World War]]|year=2014|origyear=2000|publisher=History Press|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|isbn=978-0-7509-5368-9|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040115102926/http://www.shinycapstar.com/jackson.htm Coldstream Guards memorial] - picture\n*{{Find a Grave|9987866}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Thomas Norman}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:British World War I recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:Coldstream Guards soldiers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War I]]\n[[Category:People from Swinton, South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:British Army recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Thomas Jackson}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name=Thomas Norman Jackson\n|honorific_suffix=VC\n|birth_date={{birth date|df=y|1897|2|11}}\n|death_date={{death date and age|df=y|1918|9|27|1897|2|11}}{{KIA}}\n|birth_place= [[Swinton, South Yorkshire]]\n|death_place= [[Canal du Nord]], France\n|placeofburial=Sanders Keep Military Cemetery, [[Graincourt-les-Havrincourt]]\n|image= Thomas Norman Jackson VC.jpg\n|image_size= \n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance={{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|serviceyears=1915&ndash;1918 \n|rank=[[Lance corporal|Lance Corporal]]\n|branch={{army|United Kingdom}}\n|commands= \n|unit=[[Coldstream Guards]]\n|battles= [[World War I]]\n*[[Battle of Cambrai (1917)|Battle of Cambrai]]\n*[[Hundred Days Offensive]]\n**[[Battle of the Canal du Nord]] {{KIA}}\n|awards= [[File:Victoria Cross (UK) ribbon.png|30px]] [[Victoria Cross]]\n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Thomas Norman Jackson''' [[Victoria Cross|VC]] (11 February 1897 &ndash; 27 September 1918) was an [[England|English]] soldier of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War I)|British Expeditionary Force]], and posthumous recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]], the highest military award for gallantry in the face of the enemy given to [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces, during the First World War.\n\n==Early life==\nThomas Norman Jackson was born on 11 February 1897 in [[Swinton, South Yorkshire|Swinton]] in [[South Yorkshire]] to Thomas Edwin, a worker at a supplier of mineral water, and Emma Jackson. After completing his schooling, he started working alongside his father. He later took up employment at the Great Central Locomotive Depot, based at Mexborough.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}}\n\n==First World War==\nIn November 1915, Jackson enlisted in the [[British Army]] and, in October 1917, was posted to the 1st Battalion of the [[Coldstream Guards]], which was serving in France on the [[Western Front (WWI)|Western Front]] at the time. He participated in the [[Battle of Cambrai (1917)|Battle of Cambrai]] the following month. He was later promoted to [[lance corporal]].{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}}\n\nOn 27 September 1918, during the [[Hundred Days Offensive]], the Coldstream Guards was engaged in the [[Battle of Canal du Nord]], near Graincourt. Jackson's battalion was tasked with the capture of a canal crossing. Once over the canal, it was to set up defensive positions and make contact with the adjacent 3rd Guards Battalion. On reaching the canal, the advance of Jackson's company, under the command of Captain [[Cyril Frisby]], was halted by barbed wire together with heavy fire from a German machine-gun post under the bridge on the far side of the canal. Jackson, together with Frisby and two others, got through the wire and climbed down into the canal under intense fire. With a further twelve men joining them, the post was captured.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=11\u201312}}\n\nLater in the morning, Jackson was ordered to move forward with a platoon to seize a German-held trench. He was first into the trench, and after killing two German soldiers, he in turn was killed.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}} His grave is at Sanders Keep Military Cemetery, [[Graincourt-les-Havrincourt]], which is to the west of Cambrai.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jackson, Thomas Norman |url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/338360  |website=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]] |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n \nFor his actions on 27 September 1918, Jackson was awarded the Victoria Cross (VC),{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|p=31}} one of seven that would be awarded for actions performed on 27 September.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=11\u201312}} The citation for his VC read:\n{{quote|For most conspicuous bravery and self-sacrifice in the attack across the Canal Du Nord, near Graincourt. On the morning of the 27th September, 1918, L./Cpl. Jackson was the first to volunteer to follow Capt. C. H. Frisby, Coldstream Guards, across the Canal du Nord in his rush against an enemy machine-gun post. With two comrades he followed his officer across the Canal, rushed the post, captured the two machine-guns, and so enabled the companies to advance. Later in the morning, L./Cpl. Jackson was the first to jump into a German trench which his platoon had to clear, and after doing further excellent work he was unfortunately killed. Throughout the whole day until he was killed this young N.C.O. showed the greatest valour and devotion to duty and set an inspiring example to all.|[[London Gazette]], 27 November 1918<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31034|date=26 November 1918|page=14040|supp=y }}</ref>}}\n\n[[King George V]] presented Jackson's VC to his parents in a ceremony at Buckingham Palace on 29 March 1919. Also present was Jackson's fianc\u00e9e Daisy Flatt.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|p=13}} Frisby, in attendance at the same ceremony to receive his own award of the VC for his role in the action of 27 September 1918, was able to explain to Jackson's family the circumstances of their relative's VC award. A few months later Frisby travelled to Swindon to unveil a painting commemorating Jackson.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}}\n\n==Medals==\nIn June 1969, Jackson's brother donated his medals, which in addition to the VC also included the [[British War Medal]] and Victory Medal to The Coldstream Guards Regimental Headquarters at [[Wellington Barracks, London|Wellington Barracks]] in London, where they are on display.{{sfn|Gliddon|2014|pp=32\u201334}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|last=Gliddon|first=Gerald|title=The Final Days 1918|series=[[VCs of the First World War]]|year=2014|origyear=2000|publisher=History Press|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|isbn=978-0-7509-5368-9|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040115102926/http://www.shinycapstar.com/jackson.htm Coldstream Guards memorial] - picture\n*{{Find a Grave|9987866}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Thomas Norman}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:British World War I recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:Coldstream Guards soldiers]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War I]]\n[[Category:People from Swinton, South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:British Army recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Update date format tag and add authority control template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Norman_Jackson"}
{"title_page": "Patrick Walsh (investor)", "text_new": "'''Patrick Walsh''' (born December 26, 1975) is an entrepreneur and investor in the United States. He is the founder and CEO of PW Partners, LLC, an investment management firm.  Walsh is also the Chairman and Chief Executive of [[Town Sports International]], a holding company that trades on the NASDAQ under the symbol CLUB.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/commercial-clubs/town-sports-names-patrick-walsh-ceo-consolidates-coo-role|title=Town Sports Names Patrick Walsh CEO, Consolidates COO Role|date=May 4, 2017|work=Club Industry|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>  Walsh is also a member of the Board of Directors of [[BJ's Restaurants]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investors.bjsrestaurants.com/board-member/patrick-walsh|title=Patrick Walsh {{!}} Board Member {{!}} BJ's Restaurants, Inc.|website=BJ's Restaurants, Inc.|language=en|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> and [[Del Taco Restaurants]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investor.deltaco.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=Del Taco Restaurants, Inc. - Corporate Governance - Board of Directors|website=investor.deltaco.com|language=en-CA|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nWalsh was born in San Diego, California, the eldest of three brothers.  His father was in the [[U.S. Navy]] and his mother was a school teacher. \n[[File:Patrick Walsh .jpg|thumb|Patrick Walsh the 2018 EY Entrepreneur of the Year award winner in the New York region.]]\nThe Walsh family left California and moved to Boston, Massachusetts in 1977 and Walsh grew up in [[Foxboro, Massachusetts]], the home of the [[New England Patriots]]. Walsh remains a die-hard Patriots fan to this day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/get-your-mind-right-with-boston-sports-clubs-and-gronk-fitness-300378152.html|title=Get Your Mind Right with Boston Sports Clubs and Gronk Fitness|last=Clubs|first=Boston Sports|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> Walsh studied economics at [[Wesleyan University]] and played football and baseball<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.wesleyan.edu/sports/bsb/1994-95/bios/walsh_pat_bbf0|title=Pat Walsh|website=Wesleyan Athletics|language=en|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.wesleyan.edu/sports/fball/1994-95/bios/walsh_pat_0ml0|title=Pat Walsh|website=Wesleyan Athletics|language=en|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> until he suffered a severe back injury playing football. He transferred to [[Boston College]] after his freshman year and graduated with a degree in accounting. After graduation, he earned the [[Chartered Financial Analyst]] designation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarly in his career, Walsh rejected the academic [[efficient-market theory]] and adhered instead to a philosophy of [[value investing]]. Walsh enrolled in the Value Investing Executive Program at [[Columbia Business School]] to study under Professor [[Bruce Greenwald]], who carried on the teachings (albeit evolved) of [[Benjamin Graham]], the father of value investing.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Early business career==\nWalsh worked from 1998 to 2004 at Prudential Capital Group and Prudential Securities in real estate private equity and equity research; from 2004 to 2008 at Deutsche Bank as an investment banker and at a private hedge fund based in Chicago from 2008 to 2011.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bjs-restaurants-shareholders-come-to-board-agreement-1398172042|title=BJ's Restaurants, Shareholders Come to Board Agreement|last=McCarthy|first=Erin|date=April 22, 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 11, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nWalsh formed the predecessor to PW Partners, LLC in October 2011.  During Walsh's tenure in the hedge fund industry and at PW Partners he practiced corporate activism while investing in Denny's,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/04/15/dennys-slams-investors-leading-proxy-fight/|title=Denny's Slams Investors Leading Proxy Fight|work=DealBook|access-date=May 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Red Robin Gourmet Burgers,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110124005491/en/Oak-Street-Capital-Management-LLC-Addresses-Board|title=Oak Street Capital Management, LLC Addresses the Board of Red Robin Gourmet Burgers|access-date=May 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Great Wolf Resorts,<ref name=\":1\" /> Famous Dave's,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.restfinance.com/Restaurant-Finance-Across-America/July-2015/Finally-Board-Diversity-at-Famous-Daves/|title=Finally, Board Diversity at Famous Dave\u2019s - Restaurant Industry Insight and Analysis - July 2015|website=www.restfinance.com|language=en|access-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref> BJ's Restaurants<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/17/activist-investing-wont-save-this-company.aspx|title=Activist Investing Won't Save This Company|last=Quast|first=Jon|work=The Motley Fool|access-date=May 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and Del Taco Restaurants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investor.deltaco.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=Del Taco Restaurants, Inc. - Corporate Governance - Board of Directors|website=investor.deltaco.com|language=en-CA|access-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref> A 2014 article in Restaurant Finance Monitor stated that \"each of the chains with which he has become involved have thrived on Wall Street in his wake.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.restfinance.com/Restaurant-Finance-Across-America/March-2014/Activist-Bug-Bites-BJs-Restaurants/|title=Activist Bug Bites BJ's Restaurants - Restaurant Industry Insight and Analysis - March 2014|website=www.restfinance.com|language=en|access-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWalsh invested in Town Sports International and said that the fitness business had been his worst investment.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/antoinegara/2015/07/29/patrick-walsh-dennys-red-robin-bjs-restaurants-new-york-sports-clubs/#314f5b001d93|title=Meet Patrick Walsh, The Do-It-Yourself Hedge Fund Activist You've Never Heard Of|last=Gara|first=Antoine|work=Forbes|access-date=May 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''Town Sports International Holdings'''\n\nIn June 2015 Walsh was named Chairman of the Board of Town Sports International Holdings. The Company was burning $5 million a month and was in the midst of 17 consecutive quarters of same-store sales declines.  The Company was burdened with $300 million of debt that could not be repaid with the current levels of cash flow. This led Moody's rating agency to describe Town's capital structure as \"untenable\" and they downgraded the debt to a \"Caa2\" rating. The stock price declined to 92 cents per share while the Company's debt traded down to 36 cents on the dollar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moodys.com/research/Moodys-downgrades-Town-Sports-CFR-to-Caa2-outlook-negative--PR_343821|title=Moody's downgrades Town Sports' CFR to Caa2; outlook negative|date=February 16, 2016|work=Moodys.com|access-date=June 14, 2018}}</ref> In September 2016 Walsh became Chief Executive Officer.<ref name=\":0\" /> While industry experts predicted bankruptcy or a sale,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/03/06/nysc-owner-seeks-a-sale-but-alls-not-gym-dandy/|title=NYSC owner seeks a sale, but all\u2019s not gym-dandy|date=March 7, 2015|work=New York Post|access-date=May 11, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Walsh vowed to Town's shareholders that he would never give up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.townsportsinternational.com/static-files/da8171a6-e2e2-4cda-b82a-f2296531c66d|title=Letter from the Chairman 2015}}</ref> After 17 consecutive quarters of declines in same store sales the company then posted 5 consecutive quarters of same-store sales increases and the stock price increased more than 1,000% to $11 per share in 2018.\n\nTown Sports International started to make acquisitions in September 2017 acquiring the Lucille Roberts brand, an all woman's fitness chain.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/news/town-sports-international-acquire-lucille-roberts-health-club-business|title=Town Sports International to Acquire Lucille Roberts Health Club Business|date=July 14, 2017|work=Club Industry|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> In December 2017, Town acquired the luxury brand TMPL <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://cheddar.com/videos/building-a-tmpl-to-fitness-with-town-sports-international|title=Building a \"TMPL\" to Fitness with Town Sports International|website=Cheddar|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> and in early 2018 the Company acquired Total Woman, an all woman's fitness chain based in California.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/rlh-equity-partners-portfolio-company-total-woman-acquired-by-town-sports-international-300631093.html|title=RLH Equity Partners portfolio company, Total Woman, acquired by Town Sports International|last=Partners|first=Riordan, Lewis &amp; Haden {{!}} Equity|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> Since taking over as CEO Walsh has overseen acquisitions of more than 30 clubs.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/news/town-sports-international-reports-8-million-increase-q1-2018-revenue|title=Town Sports International Reports $8 Million Increase in Q1 2018 Revenue|date=April 30, 2018|work=Club Industry|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWalsh's writings include his annual letters to shareholders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.townsportsinternational.com/corporate-governance/letter-from-the-chairman|title=Letters From the Chairman {{!}} Town Sports International Holdings, Inc.|website=Town Sports International Holdings, Inc.|language=en|access-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Walsh was chosen as an [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award]]s 2018 New York Finalist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ey.com/us/en/about-us/entrepreneurship/entrepreneur-of-the-year/met-ny_article_regional_finalists|title=Meet the 2018 Finalists}}</ref> On June 12, 2018 Walsh was selected as the winner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ey-announces-winners-for-the-entrepreneur-of-the-year-2018-new-york-award-300665597.html|title=EY Announces Winners for the Entrepreneur Of The Year\u00ae 2018 New York Award|last=EY|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego]]\n[[Category:People from Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:CFA charterholders]]\n", "text_old": "'''Patrick Walsh''' (born December 26, 1975) is an entrepreneur and investor in the United States. He is the founder and CEO of PW Partners, LLC, an investment management firm.  Walsh is also the Chairman and Chief Executive of [[Town Sports International]], a holding company that trades on the NASDAQ under the symbol CLUB.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/commercial-clubs/town-sports-names-patrick-walsh-ceo-consolidates-coo-role|title=Town Sports Names Patrick Walsh CEO, Consolidates COO Role|date=May 4, 2017|work=Club Industry|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>  Walsh is also a member of the Board of Directors of [[BJ's Restaurants]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investors.bjsrestaurants.com/board-member/patrick-walsh|title=Patrick Walsh {{!}} Board Member {{!}} BJ's Restaurants, Inc.|website=BJ's Restaurants, Inc.|language=en|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> and [[Del Taco Restaurants]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investor.deltaco.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=Del Taco Restaurants, Inc. - Corporate Governance - Board of Directors|website=investor.deltaco.com|language=en-CA|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nWalsh was born in San Diego, California, the eldest of three brothers.  His father was in the [[U.S. Navy]] and his mother was a school teacher. \n[[File:Patrick Walsh .jpg|thumb|Patrick Walsh the 2018 EY Entrepreneur of the Year award winner in the New York region.]]\nThe Walsh family left California and moved to Boston, Massachusetts in 1977 and Walsh grew up in [[Foxboro, Massachusetts]], the home of the [[New England Patriots]]. Walsh remains a die-hard Patriots fan to this day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/get-your-mind-right-with-boston-sports-clubs-and-gronk-fitness-300378152.html|title=Get Your Mind Right with Boston Sports Clubs and Gronk Fitness|last=Clubs|first=Boston Sports|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> Walsh studied economics at [[Wesleyan University]] and played football and baseball<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.wesleyan.edu/sports/bsb/1994-95/bios/walsh_pat_bbf0|title=Pat Walsh|website=Wesleyan Athletics|language=en|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.wesleyan.edu/sports/fball/1994-95/bios/walsh_pat_0ml0|title=Pat Walsh|website=Wesleyan Athletics|language=en|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> until he suffered a severe back injury playing football. He transferred to [[Boston College]] after his freshman year and graduated with a degree in accounting. After graduation, he earned the [[Chartered Financial Analyst]] designation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarly in his career, Walsh rejected the academic [[efficient-market theory]] and adhered instead to a philosophy of [[value investing]]. Walsh enrolled in the Value Investing Executive Program at [[Columbia Business School]] to study under Professor [[Bruce Greenwald]], who carried on the teachings (albeit evolved) of [[Benjamin Graham]], the father of value investing.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Early business career==\nWalsh worked from 1998 to 2004 at Prudential Capital Group and Prudential Securities in real estate private equity and equity research; from 2004 to 2008 at Deutsche Bank as an investment banker and at a private hedge fund based in Chicago from 2008 to 2011.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bjs-restaurants-shareholders-come-to-board-agreement-1398172042|title=BJ's Restaurants, Shareholders Come to Board Agreement|last=McCarthy|first=Erin|date=April 22, 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 11, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nWalsh formed the predecessor to PW Partners, LLC in October 2011.  During Walsh's tenure in the hedge fund industry and at PW Partners he practiced corporate activism while investing in Denny's,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/04/15/dennys-slams-investors-leading-proxy-fight/|title=Denny's Slams Investors Leading Proxy Fight|work=DealBook|access-date=May 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Red Robin Gourmet Burgers,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110124005491/en/Oak-Street-Capital-Management-LLC-Addresses-Board|title=Oak Street Capital Management, LLC Addresses the Board of Red Robin Gourmet Burgers|access-date=May 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Great Wolf Resorts,<ref name=\":1\" /> Famous Dave's,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.restfinance.com/Restaurant-Finance-Across-America/July-2015/Finally-Board-Diversity-at-Famous-Daves/|title=Finally, Board Diversity at Famous Dave\u2019s - Restaurant Industry Insight and Analysis - July 2015|website=www.restfinance.com|language=en|access-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref> BJ's Restaurants<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/17/activist-investing-wont-save-this-company.aspx|title=Activist Investing Won't Save This Company|last=Quast|first=Jon|work=The Motley Fool|access-date=May 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> and Del Taco Restaurants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investor.deltaco.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=Del Taco Restaurants, Inc. - Corporate Governance - Board of Directors|website=investor.deltaco.com|language=en-CA|access-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref> A 2014 article in Restaurant Finance Monitor stated that \"each of the chains with which he has become involved have thrived on Wall Street in his wake.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.restfinance.com/Restaurant-Finance-Across-America/March-2014/Activist-Bug-Bites-BJs-Restaurants/|title=Activist Bug Bites BJ's Restaurants - Restaurant Industry Insight and Analysis - March 2014|website=www.restfinance.com|language=en|access-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWalsh invested in Town Sports International and said that the fitness business had been his worst investment.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/antoinegara/2015/07/29/patrick-walsh-dennys-red-robin-bjs-restaurants-new-york-sports-clubs/#314f5b001d93|title=Meet Patrick Walsh, The Do-It-Yourself Hedge Fund Activist You've Never Heard Of|last=Gara|first=Antoine|work=Forbes|access-date=May 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''Town Sports International Holdings'''\n\nIn June 2015 Walsh was named Chairman of the Board of Town Sports International Holdings. The Company was burning $5 million a month and was in the midst of 17 consecutive quarters of same-store sales declines.  The Company was burdened with $300 million of debt that could not be repaid with the current levels of cash flow. This led Moody's rating agency to describe Town's capital structure as \"untenable\" and they downgraded the debt to a \"Caa2\" rating. The stock price declined to 92 cents per share while the Company's debt traded down to 36 cents on the dollar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moodys.com/research/Moodys-downgrades-Town-Sports-CFR-to-Caa2-outlook-negative--PR_343821|title=Moody's downgrades Town Sports' CFR to Caa2; outlook negative|date=February 16, 2016|work=Moodys.com|access-date=June 14, 2018}}</ref> In September 2016 Walsh became Chief Executive Officer.<ref name=\":0\" /> While industry experts predicted bankruptcy or a sale,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/03/06/nysc-owner-seeks-a-sale-but-alls-not-gym-dandy/|title=NYSC owner seeks a sale, but all\u2019s not gym-dandy|date=March 7, 2015|work=New York Post|access-date=May 11, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Walsh vowed to Town's shareholders that he would never give up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.townsportsinternational.com/static-files/da8171a6-e2e2-4cda-b82a-f2296531c66d|title=Letter from the Chairman 2015}}</ref> After 17 consecutive quarters of declines in same store sales the company then posted 5 consecutive quarters of same-store sales increases and the stock price increased more than 1,000% to $11 per share in 2018.\n\nTown Sports International started to make acquisitions in September 2017 acquiring the Lucille Roberts brand, an all woman's fitness chain.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/news/town-sports-international-acquire-lucille-roberts-health-club-business|title=Town Sports International to Acquire Lucille Roberts Health Club Business|date=July 14, 2017|work=Club Industry|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> In December 2017, Town acquired the luxury brand TMPL <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://cheddar.com/videos/building-a-tmpl-to-fitness-with-town-sports-international|title=Building a \"TMPL\" to Fitness with Town Sports International|website=Cheddar|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> and in early 2018 the Company acquired Total Woman, an all woman's fitness chain based in California.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/rlh-equity-partners-portfolio-company-total-woman-acquired-by-town-sports-international-300631093.html|title=RLH Equity Partners portfolio company, Total Woman, acquired by Town Sports International|last=Partners|first=Riordan, Lewis &amp; Haden {{!}} Equity|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> Since taking over as CEO Walsh has overseen acquisitions of more than 30 clubs.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/news/town-sports-international-reports-8-million-increase-q1-2018-revenue|title=Town Sports International Reports $8 Million Increase in Q1 2018 Revenue|date=April 30, 2018|work=Club Industry|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWalsh's writings include his annual letters to shareholders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.townsportsinternational.com/corporate-governance/letter-from-the-chairman|title=Letters From the Chairman {{!}} Town Sports International Holdings, Inc.|website=Town Sports International Holdings, Inc.|language=en|access-date=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Walsh was chosen as an [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award]]s 2018 New York Finalist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ey.com/us/en/about-us/entrepreneurship/entrepreneur-of-the-year/met-ny_article_regional_finalists|title=Meet the 2018 Finalists}}</ref> On June 12, 2018 Walsh was selected as the winner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ey-announces-winners-for-the-entrepreneur-of-the-year-2018-new-york-award-300665597.html|title=EY Announces Winners for the Entrepreneur Of The Year\u00ae 2018 New York Award|last=EY|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Controversy over handling of COVID-19 shutdown'''\n\nIn response to government mandates to mitigate the spread of [[COVID-19]], all Town Sports International locations were temporarily closed on March 16, 2020. All non-executive staff were subsequently terminated<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonmagazine.com/health/2020/03/19/boston-sports-clubs-coronavirus/|title=Boston Sports Clubs Laid Off All Its Employees Monday Night|date=2020-03-19|website=Boston Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 1, members were charged monthly dues, resulting in widespread outrage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2020/04/05/nysc-continues-to-charge-membership-dues-despite-gyms-being-shut|title=NYSC Continues to Charge Membership Dues Despite Gyms Being Shut|website=www.ny1.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 3, 2020, the Attorneys General of the states of New York, Pennsylvania and the District of Columbia issued a letter <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ag.ny.gov/sites/default/files/multistate_letter_to_town_sports_international.pdf|title=Town Sports International Holdings, Inc.\u2019s Unlawful Response to the COVID-19 Pandemic and National Emergency|last=James, Shapiro, Levine|first=State Attorneys General|date=April 3, 2020|website=NY State Attorney General's Office|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>demanding Walsh immediately cease charging monthly membership fees. In email correspondence sent to members on April 8, Town Sports International [https://www.newyorksportsclubs.com/page/member-letter stated] that accounts would be frozen going forward, but did not address return of membership dues that had been charged. \n\n==References==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego]]\n[[Category:People from Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:CFA charterholders]]\n", "name_user": "74.89.140.179", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly business career:This is not relevant for this profile and not accurate)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Walsh_(investor)"}
{"title_page": "Albota", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Arge\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|name=Albota\n|image_map=\n|map_caption=\n|coordinates = {{coord|44|46|53|N|24|50|53|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Albota''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Arge\u0219 County]], in southern central [[Romania]]. It is composed of five villages: Albota, Cerbu, Fr\u0103te\u0219ti, Gura V\u0103ii and Mare\u0219.\n\n{{Arge\u0219 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Arge\u0219 County]]\n\n{{Arge\u015f-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Arge\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|name=Albota\n|image_map=\n|map_caption=\n|coordinates = {{coord|44|46|53|N|24|50|53|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Albota''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Arge\u0219 County]], in southern central [[Romania]]. It is composed of five villages: Albota, Cerbu, Fr\u0103te\u0219ti, Gura V\u0103ii and Mare\u0219.\n\n{{Arge\u015f County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Arge\u0219 County]]\n\n{{Arge\u015f-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: Arge\u015f County \u2192 Arge\u0219 County", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albota"}
